#!/usr/bin/env -S browse-tui --run-py
"""browse-git — a tig-like browser over a git repository.

Six view modes, switchable by a per-mode flag (``--commits`` /
``--status`` / ``--reflog`` / ``--branches`` / ``--stash`` /
``--worktrees``) at launch, by the backtick (`` ` ``) key at runtime, or
auto-selected from positional arguments:

  commits   recent ``git log`` — drill commit -> changed files -> diff
  status    ``git status`` working-tree entries

In commits mode the log is preceded by up to four synthetic working-change
rows — ``Untracked changes`` / ``Tracked changes`` / ``Staged changes`` /
``Conflicts`` — each shown only when non-empty and drillable into its
files. They honor the same path filter and appear only on an unscoped log
(no positional rev).
  reflog    ``git reflog`` entries
  branches  branches / remotes / tags via ``git for-each-ref``
  stash     ``git stash list``
  worktrees ``git worktree list`` — one row per worktree (main first,
            relpath ``.``), drill into that worktree's branch commit log

With ``-`` as the sole argument the recipe instead reads GIT OUTPUT
FROM STDIN: the stream is slurped to EOF before the UI starts (on a
tty: until ^D, like cat) and its type is sniffed from the first
non-blank line —

  diff      a ``diff --git`` header or ``--- a/`` hunk → an auto-expanded
            ``diff: N files +X -Y`` umbrella (a synthesised ``--stat``
            table as its preview) over one row per file block, each
            block (delta-rendered) as that row's preview
  log       ``commit <sha>`` blocks (--stat / -p included) → one commit
            row per block (sha / author / date columns + decoration
            chips), the whole block as the preview
  status    porcelain ``XY path`` lines (the ``-z`` form too) or the
            human ``On branch …`` form → the status view's leaf rows

The slurped text is the ONLY data source in this mode — git is never
run for it and no repo is required: previews come from the text,
reload (ctrl-r) re-serves the parse, and the actions that re-run git
(the `` ` `` mode picker, the ``t`` graph toggle) flash instead of
acting. ``-`` combines with no other argument or flag; empty or
unrecognized input is a clean error on stderr (exit 2) before the UI
starts. When stdin is a pipe or redirect (not a tty), this mode
auto-engages — the ``-`` is optional, so ``git diff | browse-git``
works too. ``-`` stays the explicit form, needed only to read stdin
when stdin is a tty (type/paste the output, end with ^D). Bare
``browse-git`` on a terminal (tty stdin) never reads stdin.

Every row id is a tagged tuple whose first element is a short string
``kind`` tag, so dispatch is a flat ``id[0]`` match with direct field
access — never a hex-vs-word heuristic or substring scan:

  ('commit', sha)            a commit          -> changed files (+ md refs)
  ('file', sha, path)        a file in a commit -> per-file diff; a .md file
                             also -> a browse-md launcher
  ('ref', refname)           a branch/remote/tag -> commits on that ref
  ('worktree', abspath, label)  a worktree (worktrees mode) -> the commits
                             on its branch / sha; label is the branch
                             short-name, or the short HEAD sha when detached
                             (label is the drill rev), or ``(bare)`` for a
                             bare worktree (a leaf — nothing to log)
  ('status', xy, path)       a working-tree entry -> staged/worktree diff; a
                             .md file also -> a browse-md launcher
  ('wc', bucket)             a status group (untracked/tracked/staged/conflicts)
  ('stash', n[, path])       a stash (n int), or a file in one (.md -> launcher)
  ('reflog', n, sha)         a reflog entry (n int) -> changed files
  ('md-refs', sha)           a commit's [md] References umbrella -> launcher rows
  ('launch', anchor, *spec)  a [md ↗] launcher row -> opens a .md in browse-md
  ('filler', ns, n)          an inert tree-mode connector row (meta; no children)
  ('sdiff',)                 the piped-diff --stat umbrella -> its sfile rows
  ('sfile', i, path)         a file block of a piped diff (leaf; stdin mode)
  ('slog', i)                a commit block of a piped log (leaf; stdin mode)
  ('status_clean',)          the "working tree clean" sentinel (no children)
  ('stash_none',)            the "no stashes" sentinel (no children)
  ('err',)                   an error row (no children)

Because path / refname ride as their own tuple field, a path or ref
containing ':' or '/' is never ambiguous — there is no string to
re-split.

When the ``md_doc`` plugin is importable, a commit's message is scanned for
``.md`` references that resolve in ITS tree (not the working tree) and
surfaced under a ``[md] References`` umbrella, and any ``.md`` file row gains
a ``→ browse`` launcher child; Enter on a ``[md ↗]`` launcher row opens the
document in ``browse-md`` (a committed / stashed / message-referenced blob is
piped on stdin; an on-disk working-tree file is opened by path). Without
``md_doc`` these rows are absent and ``.md`` rows stay plain leaves.

Commit rows render in columns — a yellow short-sha, a dim author and a
dim relative date — followed by the branch / remote / tag refs parsed
from ``%D`` as colored chips (HEAD + local branch, remote, ``tag:``) and
the subject last. Reflog rows keep the older chip layout (short-sha tag
+ selector / relative-date / decoration chips); file rows carry their
A/M/D/R status letter as a colored tag.

Previews honour ANSI: ``git`` emits color via ``-c color.ui=always``
and per-file diffs are rendered through ``delta`` when it is on PATH
(otherwise the git-colored diff is shown verbatim). Commit messages can
be md2ansi-colored when ``md2ansi_lib`` is importable (toggle with
``m``).

Keys: Enter opens a ``[md ↗]`` launcher row in browse-md, else flips
expand/collapse of the cursor row; `` ` `` opens the
mode picker; ``t`` toggles the commit-graph column (``--tree``); ``m``
toggles md2ansi message coloring (when available); ``E`` edits the real
working-tree file for file/status rows in $EDITOR; the built-in ``v`` /
``e`` page / edit the preview text. ``\\`` / F1 / right-click open a
context menu keyed to the cursor's git-object kind (see ``on_context_menu``).

By default (toggle off with ``--no-tree`` or the ``t`` key) the commit log has a
tig-style graph column: ``git log --graph`` does all the lane assignment
and its art is glyph-substituted and rendered after the date column, with
its connector-only FILLER lines kept as inert blank rows so the lanes line
up. The flag scopes the commit log (commits mode + the ref drill-down).

Navigation and previews are read-only; the mutating operations
(working-tree edits via ``E``, plus checkout / branch / tag / reset /
cherry-pick / revert / merge / rebase / stage / discard / stash apply /
drop) live behind the context menu, the destructive ones gated on a
confirm dialog.

In commits mode ``--all`` spans the log over every local branch (git
log's ``--branches``) — equivalent to ``browse-git $(git branch
--format='%(refname:short)')`` — instead of only HEAD's history.

Usage:
  browse-git [<dir>] [-n NUMBER] [--commits|--status|--reflog|--branches|--stash] [--no-tree] [--all] [<revs>…] [-- <paths>…]
  git diff | browse-git -      (also git log / log -p / status output)
"""

import os
import re
import shutil
import subprocess
import sys
from collections import namedtuple

from browse_tui import (
    Action, Browser, BrowserConfig, Item,
    cell_ljust, cell_width, default_row_content, recipe_argv,
    sanitize_ansi, style,
)

# Optional md2ansi_lib plugin — gates md2ansi coloring of commit messages.
try:
    from md2ansi_lib import md2ansi as _md2ansi_fn
    if not callable(_md2ansi_fn):
        _md2ansi_fn = None
except Exception:
    _md2ansi_fn = None

_MD_COLOR = _md2ansi_fn is not None  # default on when available

# Optional md_doc plugin — gates the markdown launcher rows: a commit's
# message references and any ``.md`` file row expand into ``browse-md``
# launcher targets. Inert when md_doc isn't importable, exactly like the
# md2ansi_lib gate above — ``.md`` rows then stay plain leaves and a commit
# row carries only its files. md_doc owns the launcher Item shapes + the
# embedding flags / stdin policy in ``md_doc.launch``.
try:
    import md_doc as _md_doc
except Exception:
    _md_doc = None

# Probe ``delta`` once at load (not per render): used to pipe the
# git-colored diff through delta for terminal-native rendering, and — via
# the same flag — to gate side-by-side mode + the conditional preview
# cache-drop on resize (see ``_colorize_diff`` / ``_on_resize``).
HAVE_DELTA = shutil.which('delta')

_LOG_LIMIT = 1000
_MODES = ('commits', 'status', 'reflog', 'branches', 'stash', 'worktrees')

# Glyph substitution for ``git log --graph`` art (tree mode). Maps git's
# ASCII art to box-drawing / dot glyphs: every node ('*') becomes the same
# dot so git's connectors — not the node shape — convey merges. Built once
# as a str.translate table (see ``_graph_translate``). The art carries git's
# own ANSI colour (``--color=always``), so the substitution is applied only
# to the plain-text runs *between* SGR sequences (see ``_graph_translate`` /
# ``_SGR_RE``) — never to a byte inside an ``\e[…m`` escape.
_GRAPH_GLYPHS = {
    '*': '•',     # commit node           -> bullet (U+2022)
    '|': '│',     # vertical lane         -> box vertical (U+2502)
    #'/': '╱',     # ascending diagonal    -> light up-right diag (U+2571)
    #'\\': '╲',    # descending diagonal   -> light down-right diag (U+2572)
    #'_': '─',     # horizontal connector  -> box horizontal (U+2500)
    '_': '▁',     # horizontal connector  -> lower eights block
}
_GRAPH_TABLE = str.maketrans(_GRAPH_GLYPHS)

# A complete SGR sequence ``\e[ <params> m``. The param class ``[^@-~]*``
# exactly mirrors the kept-set of the framework ``sanitize_ansi`` (a CSI whose
# final byte is ``m``), so EVERY sequence that survives sanitise is matched
# here — not just the ``[0-9;]`` params real git emits. ``_graph_translate``
# splits on this pattern to glyph-substitute the plain runs while passing each
# SGR token through verbatim — guaranteeing no substitution lands inside an
# escape and no colour run is split.
_SGR_RE = re.compile(r'\x1b\[[^@-~]*m')

# git's default diff colors, used raw for the synthesised stat counts
# (``_stat_counts``) and the umbrella row title's totals — green added,
# red removed, then a reset. Complete SGR sequences, so they survive the
# framework ``sanitize_ansi`` (and the row-text / preview ANSI-aware
# truncation); the framework strips them when ANSI is off.
_GREEN = '\033[32m'
_RED = '\033[31m'
_RESET = '\033[m'

# Module-level state, all set in main() before the Browser launches.
_log_limit = _LOG_LIMIT
_mode = 'commits'
_tree_mode = True  # --tree / 't' — render git's commit graph as a column (default on)
_browser = None  # set in main() — used for preview-width lookup
_prev_pw = None  # last preview width seen by _on_resize (main-thread only)
_revs = []       # positional revisions scoping commits mode
_paths = []      # positional pathspecs scoping commits mode
_all_branches = False  # --all — span the commits log over every local branch

# Detail-display mode (number keys 1/2/3) — selects which LEADING columns
# ``git_row_content`` emits before the graph/chips/subject (mirrors
# browse-fs):
#   3 = sha · author · date · subject (default, full metadata)
#   2 = sha · subject               (drop author + date)
#   1 = subject only                (drop sha + author + date)
# Switched by the ``1`` / ``2`` / ``3`` Actions (``_set_display_mode``), each
# flashing the mode and refreshing. The column STRINGS are always stored on
# every commit Item; the mode only gates which leading columns are shown, so
# switching is a pure re-render — no refetch of the log needed. The commit
# graph column (``_tree_mode`` / ``t``) is INDEPENDENT of this mode and still
# emitted in every display mode when graph mode is on.
_DISPLAY_MODE = 3

# ``browse-git -`` (stdin) state, set once by ``_ingest_stdin`` before the
# Browser launches. ``_STDIN_KIND`` doubles as the mode flag: ``None`` is
# the normal repo mode; 'diff' / 'log' / 'status' select the stdin root
# builders and gate every path that would otherwise run git.
_STDIN_KIND = None   # None | 'diff' | 'log' | 'status'
_STDIN_ROWS = []     # per-row parsed spec (kind-specific tuples, see parsers)
_STDIN_BLOCKS = []   # per-row verbatim slice of the slurped text (previews)


# ---- argv helper ---------------------------------------------------------


def _pop_limit_arg(default):
    """Pop ``-n NUMBER`` (or ``-n=NUMBER``) out of ``sys.argv`` and return it.

    Removed before Browser.run() sees the argv so the recipe's own knob
    doesn't leak into the help-flag auto-detect or the positional
    classification below. Falls back to ``default`` if the flag is
    absent or its value isn't an int.
    """
    i = 1
    while i < len(sys.argv):
        a = sys.argv[i]
        if a == '-n' and i + 1 < len(sys.argv):
            try:
                n = int(sys.argv[i + 1])
            except ValueError:
                i += 1
                continue
            del sys.argv[i:i + 2]
            return n
        if a.startswith('-n='):
            try:
                n = int(a[3:])
            except ValueError:
                i += 1
                continue
            del sys.argv[i]
            return n
        i += 1
    return default


def _pop_mode_flag():
    """Pop a per-mode flag (``--commits`` / ``--status`` / …) out of ``sys.argv``.

    The accepted flags are derived from ``_MODES`` — one ``--{mode}`` per
    mode — so appending a mode there grows the flag set for free. Every
    occurrence is removed (so a flag never leaks into the positional
    classifier), mirroring ``_pop_tree_arg`` / ``_pop_all_arg``'s in-place
    argv editing. Returns the single chosen mode name, or ``None`` if none
    appears. Selecting more than one DISTINCT mode is fatal (stderr + exit
    2) — the modes are mutually exclusive.
    """
    flag_to_mode = {f'--{m}': m for m in _MODES}
    chosen = set()
    i = 1
    while i < len(sys.argv):
        m = flag_to_mode.get(sys.argv[i])
        if m is not None:
            chosen.add(m)
            del sys.argv[i]
        else:
            i += 1
    if len(chosen) > 1:
        sys.stderr.write(
            'browse-git: choose at most one mode flag '
            f'({", ".join("--" + m for m in _MODES)})\n')
        sys.exit(2)
    return chosen.pop() if chosen else None


def _pop_tree_arg(default):
    """Pop the ``--tree`` / ``--no-tree`` toggle out of ``sys.argv``.

    Returns ``True`` for ``--tree``, ``False`` for ``--no-tree``, or
    ``default`` when neither appears. Every occurrence is removed (so the
    flag never leaks into the positional classifier) and the LAST one wins,
    so ``--tree --no-tree`` resolves to off. Mirrors ``_pop_mode_flag``'s
    in-place argv editing.
    """
    chosen = default
    i = 1
    while i < len(sys.argv):
        a = sys.argv[i]
        if a == '--tree':
            chosen = True
            del sys.argv[i]
        elif a == '--no-tree':
            chosen = False
            del sys.argv[i]
        else:
            i += 1
    return chosen


def _pop_all_arg():
    """Pop the ``--all`` flag out of ``sys.argv``; return ``True`` if present.

    ``--all`` spans the commits-mode log over every local branch — equivalent
    to launching ``browse-git $(git branch --format='%(refname:short)')``,
    realised as ``git log --branches`` (see ``_commits_root``) so it also
    stays correct on a detached HEAD, where that branch-name expansion would
    feed a bogus ``(HEAD detached …)`` token to the positional classifier.
    Every occurrence is removed (so the flag never reaches the positional
    classifier or ``Browser.run()``); mirrors ``_pop_tree_arg``'s in-place
    argv editing.
    """
    found = False
    i = 1
    while i < len(sys.argv):
        if sys.argv[i] == '--all':
            found = True
            del sys.argv[i]
        else:
            i += 1
    return found


def _pop_repo_dir():
    """Honor a leading directory positional that points at another repo.

    ``browse-git <dir>`` should browse the repo at ``<dir>`` even when the
    cwd is unrelated (or not a repo at all). If the first non-flag
    positional is a directory whose git work tree differs from the cwd's,
    ``chdir`` into that tree and drop the arg from ``sys.argv`` so it isn't
    re-read as a pathspec by ``_classify_positionals``. All later git
    invocations then run against the new cwd.

    A directory that is a *subdir of the current repo* resolves to the same
    toplevel, so it's left in place to keep working as a pathspec filter.
    Runs before the precondition check so launching from outside a repo
    still works. Only the leading positional is considered; trailing dir
    args stay pathspecs.
    """
    i = 1
    while i < len(sys.argv):
        a = sys.argv[i]
        if a == '--':
            return
        if a.startswith('-'):
            i += 1
            continue
        if not os.path.isdir(a):
            return
        top = _run_git('-C', a, 'rev-parse', '--show-toplevel')
        if top.returncode != 0:
            return
        cwd_top = _run_git('rev-parse', '--show-toplevel')
        if cwd_top.returncode == 0 and cwd_top.stdout == top.stdout:
            return
        os.chdir(top.stdout.strip())
        del sys.argv[i]
        return


# ---- subprocess + colorization helpers -----------------------------------


def _run_git(*args):
    """Run ``git args…``; return CompletedProcess (returncode + stdout/err).

    Uses ``check=False`` so the recipe can branch on ``returncode``
    rather than raise. Errors surface as Items / preview text. A missing
    git binary is folded into the same shape — a failed CompletedProcess
    (rc 127, the command-not-found convention) instead of a
    ``FileNotFoundError`` — so every caller's existing ``rc != 0``
    handling covers the gitless environment too. That is in-contract:
    ``browse-git -`` starts without the git-on-PATH precondition, and a
    mid-session call there (``E``'s work-tree-root resolve) must degrade,
    not take down the key dispatch.
    """
    try:
        return subprocess.run(['git'] + list(args), check=False,
                              capture_output=True, text=True)
    except FileNotFoundError:
        return subprocess.CompletedProcess(
            ['git', *args], 127, stdout='', stderr='git not found on PATH')


def _git_color(*args):
    """Return colored output of ``git -c color.ui=always <args>``.

    Forces SGR even though stdout is a pipe; used for ``show --stat``,
    per-file diffs, and ref summaries whose color should always be present
    regardless of the ``delta`` fallback path.

    Prefers stdout whenever it's non-empty, only falling back to stderr
    when stdout is empty. This keeps ``git diff --no-index`` working: that
    command exits non-zero whenever the files differ (always, for
    ``/dev/null`` vs a real file) yet still writes the diff to stdout, so a
    plain ``rc == 0`` gate would discard a perfectly good untracked diff.
    """
    result = _run_git('-c', 'color.ui=always', *args)
    return result.stdout or result.stderr


def _colorize_diff(raw):
    """Render an already-git-colored diff for the preview pane.

    Contract: ``raw`` is the diff text produced *once* by the caller,
    already SGR-colored (e.g. via ``_git_color('show', …)`` which runs
    with ``color.ui=always``). When ``delta`` is on PATH (``HAVE_DELTA``)
    the text is piped through it for terminal-native rendering; ``delta``
    parses the colored diff and re-emits its own SGR. When ``delta`` is
    absent the git-colored ``raw`` is returned unchanged — so either path
    yields ANSI-bearing text and the caller never has to generate the
    diff twice.

    ``--no-gitconfig`` ignores the user's theme and suppresses the OSC-8
    hyperlink emission the preview pane can't render; ``--paging never``
    stops delta spawning a pager off-tty; ``--width`` matches the pane
    (read from the module-level ``_browser`` since ``get_preview`` gets
    no ``ctx``). At a wide pane (``width >= 160``) delta lays the diff out
    side-by-side, splitting that same ``--width`` into two columns
    (``--line-fill-method=spaces`` pads each side so the gutter aligns) —
    this render is width-dependent, which ``_on_resize`` accounts for.
    """
    if HAVE_DELTA:
        width = (_browser.preview_width if _browser else 0) or 80
        argv = ['delta', '--no-gitconfig', '--paging', 'never',
                '--width', str(width)]
        if width >= 160:
            # Wide pane: two columns out of the one --width above.
            argv += ['--side-by-side', '--line-fill-method=spaces']
        proc = subprocess.run(
            argv, input=raw, capture_output=True, text=True, check=False)
        if proc.returncode == 0:
            return proc.stdout
        # delta failed unexpectedly — fall back to the git-colored text.
    return raw


def _md_message(text):
    """Return ``text`` md2ansi-colored when the toggle + library allow it."""
    if _MD_COLOR and _md2ansi_fn is not None and text:
        try:
            width = (_browser.preview_width if _browser else 0) or 80
            return _md2ansi_fn(text, line_width=width)
        except Exception:
            pass
    return text


# ---- markdown launcher rows ----------------------------------------------

# Two launch targets, surfaced via the shared ``md_doc`` launcher Items:
#
#   * a commit's MESSAGE references — a ``[md] References`` umbrella prepended
#     to the commit's files, its launcher rows opening each referenced ``.md``
#     resolved against THE COMMIT TREE (not the working tree);
#   * any ``.md`` FILE row — a single ``→ browse`` launcher child opening that
#     file (from the working tree for a real on-disk path, or extracted from
#     its revision for a committed / stashed blob).
#
# The launcher-row id is md_doc's generic ``('launch', anchor, *spec)``: the
# ``anchor`` is one element (a commit sha for an umbrella row, or the parent
# row's own id-tuple for a ``.md`` file child) so the launch ``spec`` is always
# ``id[2:]`` regardless of the anchor's internals. ``spec`` is OUR opaque,
# discriminator-led tuple that ``on_enter`` decodes to choose path-vs-stdin:
#
#   ('blob', rev, path)  — extract ``git show rev:path`` and launch via stdin
#                          (``rev`` is a commit sha or a ``stash@{n}`` selector)
#   ('wtfile', abspath)  — launch the on-disk working-tree file by path
#
# Inert unless ``md_doc`` imported (the launcher Items live in its
# browse_tui-aware half); ``_md_launchable`` is the single gate the builders
# and the get_children dispatch share.

_MD_EXTS = ('.md', '.MD')


def _md_launchable(path):
    """True if ``path`` is a markdown file we offer a browse-md launcher for.

    Gated on ``md_doc`` being importable — absent it the whole launcher
    feature is inert and ``.md`` file rows stay plain leaves. Mirrors
    browse-fs's gate so the two recipes agree on what is launchable.
    """
    return _md_doc is not None and isinstance(path, str) and path.endswith(_MD_EXTS)


def _repo_root():
    """Work-tree root via ``git rev-parse --show-toplevel``, or ``''``.

    The ``--root`` resolution base for every launched document (so links
    inside the opened markdown resolve against the repo). Empty outside a
    repo / when git is absent — the launch still works, only refs in a
    stdin-launched document then can't resolve. Same resolve ``E`` uses for
    the working-tree path.
    """
    result = _run_git('rev-parse', '--show-toplevel')
    return result.stdout.strip() if result.returncode == 0 else ''


def _shell_cwd(item_id):
    """Directory a "Run shell here" should open in for the cursor row.

    A ``('worktree', abspath, …)`` row (the only "a worktree" kind) opens its
    own working directory; every other row opens the repo's work-tree root
    (``'.'`` when outside a repo / gitless, so the shell still launches).
    """
    if (isinstance(item_id, tuple) and len(item_id) >= 2
            and item_id[0] == 'worktree'):
        return item_id[1]
    return _repo_root() or '.'


def _run_shell(ctx, cwd):
    """Open an interactive ``$SHELL`` with ``cwd`` as the working directory.

    ``ctx.run_external`` has no ``cwd`` knob, so the directory change rides in a
    shell-string command (run via ``sh -c``): ``cd <dir> && exec <$SHELL> -l
    -i``. ``exec`` replaces the wrapping ``sh`` with the user's shell so signals
    / the exit code pass through; ``-l -i`` makes it a login interactive shell
    that loads the same startup files (and thus the real prompt) as the user's
    normal terminal. ``$SHELL`` defaults to ``sh`` and may carry args
    (``bash --login``), which the shell-string honours verbatim.
    """
    import shlex
    shell = os.environ.get('SHELL') or 'sh'
    ctx.run_external(f'cd {shlex.quote(cwd)} && exec {shell} -l -i')


def _blob_text(rev, path):
    """Contents of ``path`` at ``rev`` (``git show rev:path``), or ``None``.

    ``rev`` is a commit sha or a ``stash@{n}`` selector. ``None`` on any git
    failure (path absent from the revision, gitless) so the caller flashes
    rather than launching an empty document.
    """
    result = _run_git('show', f'{rev}:{path}')
    return result.stdout if result.returncode == 0 else None


def _commit_md_refs(sha):
    """Distinct ``.md`` refs in commit ``sha``'s message resolving in its TREE.

    Scans the full commit message (``git show -s --format=%B``) for ``.md``
    tokens via ``md_doc.find_md_refs``, then resolves each against the COMMIT
    TREE — ``git cat-file -e sha:<token>`` — NOT the filesystem (the working
    tree may not match the commit, and a committed doc need not exist on disk
    at all). Returns ordered, de-duplicated ``(path, label)`` pairs: ``path``
    is the repo-relative token that exists in the tree (a leading ``./`` is
    normalised off so the launch ``rev:path`` and the label agree) and
    ``label`` is its display form (``md_doc.ref_label`` against the repo
    root). ``[]`` when the message has no resolving refs (so the umbrella is
    omitted) or md_doc / git is unavailable.
    """
    if _md_doc is None:
        return []
    msg = _run_git('show', '-s', '--format=%B', sha)
    if msg.returncode != 0:
        return []
    root = _repo_root()
    seen = set()
    out = []
    for token in _md_doc.find_md_refs(msg.stdout):
        # ``git show`` / ``cat-file`` take a repo-root-relative path; a leading
        # ``./`` is accepted by git but would split the dedup key from the
        # label, so normalise it off. Absolute / ``..`` tokens simply fail the
        # existence probe and fall away.
        path = token[2:] if token.startswith('./') else token
        if path in seen:
            continue
        if _run_git('cat-file', '-e', f'{sha}:{path}').returncode != 0:
            continue
        seen.add(path)
        label = _md_doc.ref_label(os.path.join(root, path), root) if root else path
        out.append((path, label))
    return out


def _commit_md_prefix(sha):
    """The ``[md] References`` umbrella for commit ``sha``, or ``[]``.

    Prepended to the commit's file rows when its message references any ``.md``
    file that resolves in the commit tree (``_commit_md_refs``). The umbrella
    is an expandable grouping row (``md_doc.references_umbrella``); its launcher
    children are built lazily when it expands (``_commit_md_children``), so the
    message is scanned once here to decide whether to show it and again on
    expand to build the rows — each scan self-contained, no shared state.
    """
    if _md_doc is None or not _commit_md_refs(sha):
        return []
    return [_md_doc.references_umbrella(sha)]


def _commit_md_children(sha):
    """Launcher rows under a commit's ``[md] References`` umbrella.

    One ``[md ↗]`` row per resolving message ref (``_commit_md_refs``), each
    carrying a ``('blob', sha, path)`` spec so ``on_enter`` extracts
    ``git show sha:path`` and launches it via stdin. Titled by the ref's
    display label; the anchor is the commit sha.
    """
    return [_md_doc.launcher_row(sha, ('blob', sha, path), label)
            for path, label in _commit_md_refs(sha)]


def _md_file_children(item_id, spec):
    """The single ``→ browse`` launcher child for a ``.md`` file row.

    Shared by the committed / working-tree / stash file rows: each ``.md`` row
    gets exactly one launcher child, anchored on the row's own id (so sibling
    rows stay distinct) and carrying the caller's opaque ``spec`` — a
    ``('blob', rev, path)`` for a revision blob or a ``('wtfile', abspath)``
    for an on-disk file. Titled ``→ browse`` (the lone child needs no
    path label — its parent already names the file).
    """
    return [_md_doc.launcher_row(item_id, spec, '→ browse')]


def _md_launch_preview(spec):
    """Markdown preview for a ``('launch', anchor, *spec)`` row.

    ``spec`` (the launcher id's ``[2:]``) names the document the row would
    open: a ``('wtfile', abspath)`` on-disk file or a ``('blob', rev, path)``
    revision blob (``git show rev:path``). Rendered through ``_md_message``
    (md2ansi when the toggle/library allow, else raw) — the same colored-
    markdown view browse-md would open, so the preview matches the launch.
    Returns ``''`` when the target is unreadable / spec is unrecognised.
    """
    if len(spec) == 2 and spec[0] == 'wtfile':
        try:
            with open(spec[1], 'rb') as f:
                text = f.read().decode('utf-8', errors='replace')
        except OSError as e:
            return f'[error] {e}'
        return _md_message(text)
    if len(spec) == 3 and spec[0] == 'blob':
        text = _blob_text(spec[1], spec[2])
        return _md_message(text) if text is not None else ''
    return ''


def _parse_decorations(deco, remotes=None):
    """Parse a ``%D`` decoration string into ``[(text, style)]`` chips.

    ``%D`` is the bare decoration form (no surrounding parens), e.g.
    ``HEAD -> main, tag: v1.0, origin/main, feature/x``. Tokens are split
    on ``', '`` and classified:

      * ``HEAD -> name`` → a ``HEAD`` chip plus the pointed-at branch
        (``HEAD`` styled green, the branch by its own kind);
      * ``tag: name``    → yellow ``name`` chip;
      * a remote-tracking ref (leading segment is a known remote, e.g.
        ``origin/main``) → blue;
      * any other token  → a local branch, cyan (so a local branch named
        ``feature/x`` is NOT mistaken for a remote).

    ``remotes`` is the set of remote names (``{'origin'}``) used to tell a
    remote-tracking ref from a slash-bearing local branch; when ``None``
    it's looked up once via ``git remote``. ``HEAD`` alone (detached)
    yields a single green ``HEAD`` chip. An empty decoration yields no
    chips. The framework's chip styler only honours named palette styles,
    so the HEAD chip uses ``'green'`` (the palette has no bold-green
    entry).
    """
    chips = []
    deco = (deco or '').strip()
    if not deco:
        return chips
    if remotes is None:
        remotes = _git_remotes()
    for token in deco.split(', '):
        token = token.strip()
        if not token:
            continue
        if token.startswith('HEAD -> '):
            chips.append(('HEAD', 'green'))
            branch = token[len('HEAD -> '):].strip()
            if branch:
                chips.append((branch, _ref_style(branch, remotes)))
        elif token == 'HEAD':
            chips.append(('HEAD', 'green'))
        elif token.startswith('tag: '):
            chips.append((token[len('tag: '):].strip(), 'yellow'))
        else:
            chips.append((token, _ref_style(token, remotes)))
    return chips


def _ref_style(name, remotes):
    """Style a plain ref: remote-tracking refs blue, local branches cyan.

    A ref is remote-tracking when its leading path segment is one of the
    repo's remote names (``origin/main`` with ``origin`` a remote). A
    local branch carrying a ``/`` (``feature/x``) stays cyan.
    """
    head = name.split('/', 1)[0]
    return 'blue' if '/' in name and head in remotes else 'cyan'


_REMOTES_CACHE = None


def _git_remotes():
    """Return the set of configured remote names (cached for the session)."""
    global _REMOTES_CACHE
    if _REMOTES_CACHE is None:
        result = _run_git('remote')
        _REMOTES_CACHE = (
            set(result.stdout.split()) if result.returncode == 0 else set())
    return _REMOTES_CACHE


# Status letter → tag_style. Shared by the commit/reflog file lists
# (name-status letters) and status mode (porcelain XY → one letter).
_STATUS_LETTER_STYLE = {
    'A': 'green',
    'M': 'yellow',
    'D': 'red',
    'R': 'cyan',
    'C': 'cyan',
    'T': 'yellow',
    'U': 'red',
    '?': 'dim',
}


def _parse_name_status(text):
    """Parse ``git show --name-status`` output into ``[(status, path)]``.

    Each line is ``<STATUS>\\t<path>`` (add/modify/delete) or, for renames
    and copies, ``<STATUS>\\t<old>\\t<new>`` where ``STATUS`` carries a
    similarity score (``R100`` / ``C75``). Returns the single status
    letter and the path to display — the *new* path for renames/copies,
    which is also what the resulting ``('file', sha, path)`` id keys on.
    """
    rows = []
    for line in text.splitlines():
        if not line.strip():
            continue
        parts = line.split('\t')
        if len(parts) < 2:
            continue
        status = parts[0][:1]  # drop the similarity score on R/C
        path = parts[-1]       # new path for renames/copies; the path otherwise
        rows.append((status, path))
    return rows


def _parse_porcelain_z(data):
    """Parse ``git status --porcelain -z`` bytes-as-text into ``[(XY, path)]``.

    The ``-z`` form is NUL-terminated and never quotes paths, so paths with
    spaces / odd chars survive verbatim — chosen over the line-based
    ``--porcelain`` (which C-quotes such paths and uses an inline
    ``orig -> new`` arrow for renames).

    Each entry is ``XY<space><path>`` where ``XY`` is exactly the first two
    columns (either may be a space for one-sided changes — `` M``, ``M ``,
    ``MM``, ``??``…). For a rename/copy (``X`` is ``R`` or ``C``) git emits
    the entry's path then a SECOND NUL field carrying the old path; we keep
    the new path and skip the old one. Returns ``[(XY, new_path)]``.
    """
    fields = [f for f in data.split('\x00') if f != '']
    rows = []
    i = 0
    while i < len(fields):
        entry = fields[i]
        i += 1
        if len(entry) < 3:
            continue
        xy = entry[:2]
        path = entry[3:]  # column 3 is the separating space
        # Rename / copy: the next NUL field is the old path — consume it.
        if xy and xy[0] in ('R', 'C'):
            i += 1
        rows.append((xy, path))
    return rows


# Porcelain XY codes that flag an unmerged (conflicted) path. Either
# column being ``U``, or the matched-pair both-added / both-deleted forms
# (``AA`` / ``DD``), means git is mid-merge on this path — the entry is a
# conflict regardless of which side touched it.
_UNMERGED_CODES = frozenset({'DD', 'AU', 'UD', 'UA', 'DU', 'AA', 'UU'})


def _is_conflict(xy):
    """True when a porcelain ``XY`` code names an unmerged (conflicted) path.

    Conflict entries are the seven codes in ``_UNMERGED_CODES``; every
    other code is an ordinary staged / worktree / untracked change.
    """
    return xy in _UNMERGED_CODES


def _classify_worktree(rows):
    """Bucket ``_parse_porcelain_z`` rows into the four worktree groups.

    ``rows`` is the ``[(XY, path)]`` list from ``_parse_porcelain_z``.
    Returns a dict with four lists, each holding the ``(XY, path)`` tuples
    that belong to that group:

      * ``'conflicts'`` — unmerged codes (``_is_conflict``); a conflict
        lands here and ONLY here, never in staged / tracked, so a
        mid-merge path shows up once.
      * ``'untracked'`` — the ``??`` code.
      * ``'staged'``    — a non-conflict code whose ``X`` column is set
        (not a space, not ``?``).
      * ``'tracked'``   — a non-conflict code whose ``Y`` column is set
        (not a space, not ``?``).

    Staged and tracked are NOT exclusive: a two-sided code such as ``MM``
    (staged + unstaged modification) appears in BOTH lists.
    """
    buckets = {
        'untracked': [],
        'tracked': [],
        'staged': [],
        'conflicts': [],
    }
    for xy, path in rows:
        if _is_conflict(xy):
            buckets['conflicts'].append((xy, path))
            continue
        if xy == '??':
            buckets['untracked'].append((xy, path))
            continue
        x, y = xy[0], xy[1] if len(xy) > 1 else ' '
        if x not in (' ', '?'):
            buckets['staged'].append((xy, path))
        if y not in (' ', '?'):
            buckets['tracked'].append((xy, path))
    return buckets


def _status_tag(xy):
    """Pick the one-letter status tag for a porcelain ``XY`` code.

    Untracked (``??``) shows ``?``; otherwise the staged column ``X`` when
    set, else the worktree column ``Y``. Returns ``''`` for an all-space
    code (shouldn't occur in porcelain output).
    """
    if xy == '??':
        return '?'
    x, y = xy[0], xy[1] if len(xy) > 1 else ' '
    if x != ' ':
        return x
    if y != ' ':
        return y
    return ''


def _status_diff_plan(xy, path):
    """Map a porcelain ``XY`` + path to the diff command(s) to render.

    Returns a list of ``(header, argv)`` pairs — the per-file diff(s) whose
    colored output makes up the status-leaf preview:

      * conflict (an unmerged code)        → ``diff -- <path>``
      * staged (``X`` set and not ``?``)   → ``diff --cached -- <path>``
      * worktree (``Y`` set and not ``?``) → ``diff -- <path>``
      * untracked (``??``)                 → ``diff --no-index -- /dev/null <path>``

    Unmerged codes (``_is_conflict``) are handled FIRST, ahead of the
    X/Y split, so a conflicted leaf shows a single ``diff -- <path>`` —
    which git renders in combined (``--cc``) form for an unmerged path —
    rather than two empty staged/worktree sections.

    A two-sided code (``MM``) yields BOTH the staged and worktree diffs,
    each under its own header. The ``argv`` lists are the args passed to
    ``git`` (color is applied by the caller via ``_git_color``). Note the
    ``--no-index`` diff exits non-zero whenever the files differ — the
    caller must NOT gate on the return code.
    """
    if _is_conflict(xy):
        return [('conflict', ['diff', '--', path])]
    if xy == '??':
        return [('untracked', ['diff', '--no-index', '--', '/dev/null', path])]
    x, y = xy[0], xy[1] if len(xy) > 1 else ' '
    plan = []
    if x not in (' ', '?'):
        plan.append(('staged', ['diff', '--cached', '--', path]))
    if y not in (' ', '?'):
        plan.append(('unstaged', ['diff', '--', path]))
    return plan


def _status_leaf(xy, path):
    """Build one ``('status', xy, path)`` working-tree leaf Item.

    Shared by ``_status_root`` (status mode) and ``_worktree_files`` (the
    commits-mode worktree groups) so both render a working-tree entry the
    same way: a non-expandable leaf titled by its path, tagged with the
    one-letter status (``_status_tag``) colored by kind. The leaf preview
    is the staged / worktree / untracked diff chosen from the ``XY`` code.
    """
    tag = _status_tag(xy)
    return Item(id=('status', xy, path), title=path,
                tag=tag,
                tag_style=_STATUS_LETTER_STYLE.get(tag, ''),
                has_children=_md_launchable(path))


# Worktree groups for commits mode — the ordered (bucket, label) pairs
# defining BOTH the display order of the synthetic status rows and their
# titles. Mirrors the four ``_classify_worktree`` buckets.
_WC_GROUPS = [
    ('untracked', 'Untracked changes'),
    ('tracked', 'Tracked changes'),
    ('staged', 'Staged changes'),
    ('conflicts', 'Conflicts'),
]


def _err_item(msg):
    """Return a single non-expandable error Item to render in the list."""
    return [Item(id=('err',), title=msg, tag='err', tag_style='red')]


# ---- stdin ingest (browse-git -) -------------------------------------------
#
# ``browse-git -`` slurps git output from stdin BEFORE the UI starts and
# builds the matching tree from that text alone. Classification and field
# extraction always look at the SGR-stripped line (``_SGR_RE``) so input
# piped with ``--color=always`` sniffs / splits identically, while the
# stored blocks keep the original colour for the preview pane.

# First line of ``git status --porcelain``: two status columns (at least
# one of them set — XY is never two spaces) + a space + the path. The
# column class is porcelain v1's letter set; '?' / '!' cover untracked /
# ignored entries.
_PORCELAIN_LINE_RE = re.compile(r'(?:[MTADRCU?!][ MTADRCU?!]| [MTADRCU?!]) \S')

# A ``commit <sha>`` block header, with the optional ``(decorations)``
# suffix the human log emits — used both to sniff/split log input and to
# pull the sha + ``%D``-style decoration string out of a block.
_COMMIT_LINE_RE = re.compile(r'commit ([0-9a-f]{7,40})\b(?: \((.*)\))?')

# A ``diff --git a/… b/…`` per-file header (block splitter for diff input).
_DIFF_HEADER_RE = re.compile(r'diff --git ')


def _sniff_stdin_kind(text):
    """Classify slurped stdin by its first non-blank line.

    Returns 'diff' (a ``diff --git`` header or a bare ``--- a/`` hunk
    fragment), 'log' (a ``commit <sha>`` block), 'porcelain' (a status
    ``XY path`` line — the NUL ``-z`` form matches too, its first "line"
    being the whole record stream), 'human' (``git status`` prose
    starting ``On branch`` / ``HEAD detached``), or ``None`` when the
    first non-blank line is none of those (including empty input). The
    match is on the SGR-stripped line, so colored input classifies the
    same as plain.
    """
    for line in text.splitlines():
        if not line.strip():
            continue
        plain = _SGR_RE.sub('', line)
        if plain.startswith('diff --git ') or plain.startswith('--- a/'):
            return 'diff'
        if _COMMIT_LINE_RE.match(plain):
            return 'log'
        if plain.startswith('On branch ') or plain.startswith('HEAD detached'):
            return 'human'
        if _PORCELAIN_LINE_RE.match(plain):
            return 'porcelain'
        return None
    return None


def _split_blocks(text, header_re):
    """Split ``text`` into blocks opening at lines matching ``header_re``.

    The shared splitter behind the diff (``diff --git ``) and log
    (``commit <sha>``) block builders: a new block starts at every line
    whose SGR-stripped form matches ``header_re``; everything up to the
    next header (hunks, message, --stat, -p patches…) stays in the block.
    Text before the first header — e.g. a headerless ``--- a/`` diff
    fragment — is its own leading block; whitespace-only blocks (blank
    leading lines) are dropped. Blocks keep their original lines
    verbatim, colour and all.
    """
    blocks = []
    cur = []
    for line in text.splitlines(keepends=True):
        if cur and header_re.match(_SGR_RE.sub('', line)):
            blocks.append(''.join(cur))
            cur = []
        cur.append(line)
    if cur:
        blocks.append(''.join(cur))
    return [b for b in blocks if b.strip()]


def _diff_path(p):
    """Display path from a ``---``/``+++`` header payload.

    Drops a GNU-diff trailing ``\\t<timestamp>`` part and ONE leading
    ``a/`` / ``b/`` prefix (git's diff mnemonics — a repo path that
    itself starts ``b/`` arrives as ``b/b/…`` and survives intact).
    """
    p = p.split('\t', 1)[0]
    return p[2:] if p.startswith(('a/', 'b/')) else p


def _diff_block_row(block):
    """Derive one diff block's ``(status letter, display path)``.

    The letter mirrors the recipe's name-status conventions: ``A`` for a
    new file (``new file mode`` marker, or a ``--- /dev/null`` old side),
    ``D`` for a deletion, ``R`` / ``C`` for renames / copies, ``M``
    otherwise. The display path is the NEW path — preferring the ``+++``
    header, then ``rename to`` (a pure rename has no ``---``/``+++``
    lines), then the ``---`` side (deletions), then the ``diff --git``
    header itself. All matching is on the SGR-stripped text.
    """
    lines = _SGR_RE.sub('', block).splitlines()

    def has(prefix):
        return any(l.startswith(prefix) for l in lines)

    if has('new file mode') or has('--- /dev/null'):
        letter = 'A'
    elif has('deleted file mode') or has('+++ /dev/null'):
        letter = 'D'
    elif has('rename from '):
        letter = 'R'
    elif has('copy from '):
        letter = 'C'
    else:
        letter = 'M'

    plus = minus = rename = None
    for l in lines:
        if plus is None and l.startswith('+++ ') and l[4:] != '/dev/null':
            plus = _diff_path(l[4:])
        elif minus is None and l.startswith('--- ') and l[4:] != '/dev/null':
            minus = _diff_path(l[4:])
        elif rename is None and l.startswith('rename to '):
            rename = l[len('rename to '):]
    # New path first; a deletion's name only exists on the old side.
    path = (minus or plus) if letter == 'D' else (plus or rename or minus)
    if path is None:
        m = re.match(r'diff --git a/(.*?) b/(.*)$', lines[0]) if lines else None
        path = m.group(2) if m else '(unknown file)'
    return letter, path


def _parse_stdin_diff(text):
    """Parse slurped diff text into aligned ``(rows, blocks)``.

    ``blocks[i]`` is the i-th per-file slice of the text (the preview
    source, colour preserved); ``rows[i]`` is its ``(letter, path)``
    display spec from ``_diff_block_row``.
    """
    blocks = _split_blocks(text, _DIFF_HEADER_RE)
    return [_diff_block_row(b) for b in blocks], blocks


def _diff_block_counts(block):
    """One block's ``(added, removed, is_binary)`` change counts.

    A single pass over the SGR-stripped lines, split at the first hunk
    header (``@@``) into the file-header region and the hunk body:

      * header region — nothing is counted (this is where the ``---`` /
        ``+++`` file headers live, so they are excluded by POSITION, not
        by prefix); git's binary markers (``Binary files … differ`` /
        ``GIT binary patch``) are detected here.
      * inside hunks — EVERY line starting ``+`` counts as added and
        every ``-`` as removed, exactly like ``git diff --numstat``. A
        body line whose own content starts ``+++``/``---`` (rendered
        ``++++ x`` / ``---- y`` with the diff prefix) is a normal change
        line and counts.

    A binary file yields ``(0, 0, True)`` and is never line-counted (git
    reports such files as ``Bin``, not a +/- tally). A hunkless rename or
    copy has no hunks at all, so it falls out as ``(0, 0, False)``
    naturally.
    """
    added = removed = 0
    binary = False
    in_hunk = False
    for line in _SGR_RE.sub('', block).splitlines():
        if line.startswith('@@'):
            in_hunk = True
        elif not in_hunk:
            if line.startswith(('Binary files ', 'GIT binary patch')):
                binary = True
        elif line.startswith('+'):
            added += 1
        elif line.startswith('-'):
            removed += 1
    if binary:
        return 0, 0, True
    return added, removed, False


def _diff_stat_summary(n_files, insertions, deletions):
    """git's ``N files changed, X insertions(+), Y deletions(-)`` footer.

    Mirrors git's ``print_stat_summary`` pluralisation and zero-part
    elision: the insertions clause is shown when ``insertions`` is
    non-zero OR ``deletions`` is zero, the deletions clause when
    ``deletions`` is non-zero OR ``insertions`` is zero. So a one-sided
    change drops the zero half (``…, 3 insertions(+)`` with no
    ``, 0 deletions(-)``) while an all-zero diff (e.g. binary-only) still
    prints both zero clauses, exactly as git does.
    """
    files_word = 'file' if n_files == 1 else 'files'
    parts = [f' {n_files} {files_word} changed']
    if insertions or not deletions:
        word = 'insertion' if insertions == 1 else 'insertions'
        parts.append(f'{insertions} {word}(+)')
    if deletions or not insertions:
        word = 'deletion' if deletions == 1 else 'deletions'
        parts.append(f'{deletions} {word}(-)')
    return ', '.join(parts)


def _stat_name(path, width):
    """A ``--stat`` row's path, fit to ``width`` cells (front-elided).

    A path wider than the column keeps its readable tail behind a ``...``
    prefix — the last ``width - 3`` cells of the path. No ``/``-boundary
    snapping (Option B, #938): the kept tail is whatever fits, ellipsis
    first. Shorter paths are returned as-is (no padding — the counts that
    follow don't need a fixed-width name column any more).
    """
    if cell_width(path) <= width:
        return path
    return '...' + path[cell_width(path) - (width - 3):]


def _stat_counts(added, removed, is_bin):
    """The colored ``+N -M`` (or ``Bin``) count cell for one stat row.

    Option B (#938): no histogram bars — the green ``+N`` / red ``-M``
    carry the magnitude the bars used to. A binary file shows ``Bin``
    (git reports no +/- tally for one). Both sides are always shown and
    always colored, including a zero side (``+0`` green / ``-0`` red): the
    number is the signal, so dimming a zero would only add code. Colors
    are git's diff defaults (green add / red remove); the framework strips
    them in the preview when ANSI is off (``--no-preview-ansi`` / R).
    """
    if is_bin:
        return 'Bin'
    return f'{_GREEN}+{added}{_RESET} {_RED}-{removed}{_RESET}'


def _stdin_diff_stat(width):
    """Synthesised stat table for the piped diff, fit to ``width``.

    Re-derives the per-file counts from ``_STDIN_BLOCKS`` (aligned with
    ``_STDIN_ROWS``) and lays them out as ``<path> | +N -M`` rows + the
    standard summary footer (``_diff_stat_summary``). Option B (#938): no
    ``git diff --stat`` byte-for-byte match and no histogram bars — the
    colored counts (``_stat_counts``: green ``+N`` / red ``-M``, ``Bin``
    for a binary file, ``+0 -0`` for a hunkless rename/copy) carry the
    magnitude instead.

    ``width`` is only used to front-elide an over-long path
    (``_stat_name``); the counts always fit. It is the CURRENT preview
    width (``ctx.preview_width`` / ``_browser.preview_width``), and the
    umbrella preview re-renders on a width change via ``_on_resize`` so a
    long path re-fits to the pane.
    """
    files = [(path, *_diff_block_counts(_STDIN_BLOCKS[i]))
             for i, (_letter, path) in enumerate(_STDIN_ROWS)]
    if not files:
        return _diff_stat_summary(0, 0, 0)

    out = []
    for path, added, removed, is_bin in files:
        # The counts cell is short and ANSI-only-wide; reserve a small,
        # fixed budget for it so the name truncation tracks the pane.
        name = _stat_name(path, max(width - 16, 10))
        out.append(f' {name} | {_stat_counts(added, removed, is_bin)}')

    insertions = sum(a for _p, a, _r, b in files if not b)
    deletions = sum(r for _p, _a, r, b in files if not b)
    out.append(_diff_stat_summary(len(files), insertions, deletions))
    return '\n'.join(out)


def _log_block_row(block):
    """Derive one log block's ``(sha, author, date, subject, deco)``.

    ``sha`` + the parenthesized decoration string come off the ``commit``
    header line; ``author`` is the ``Author:`` name with the ``<email>``
    dropped; ``date`` is the ``Date:`` payload verbatim; ``subject`` is
    the first non-blank message line (git indents the message by four
    spaces, which nothing else in log / --stat / -p output uses, and the
    scan stops there — --stat / -p content never reaches the fields).
    Headers a variant may omit yield ``''`` for that field.
    """
    sha = deco = author = date = subject = ''
    for line in _SGR_RE.sub('', block).splitlines():
        if not sha:
            m = _COMMIT_LINE_RE.match(line)
            if m:
                sha, deco = m.group(1), m.group(2) or ''
                continue
        if line.startswith('Author:'):
            author = line[len('Author:'):].strip().split(' <')[0]
        elif line.startswith('Date:'):
            date = line[len('Date:'):].strip()
        elif line.startswith('    ') and line.strip():
            subject = line.strip()
            break
    return sha, author, date, subject, deco


def _parse_stdin_log(text):
    """Parse slurped ``git log`` text into aligned ``(rows, blocks)``.

    ``blocks[i]`` is the i-th whole-commit slice (message and any --stat
    / -p payload included — the preview source); ``rows[i]`` is its
    ``(sha, author, date, subject, deco)`` spec from ``_log_block_row``.
    """
    blocks = _split_blocks(text, _COMMIT_LINE_RE)
    return [_log_block_row(b) for b in blocks], blocks


def _parse_porcelain_lines(text):
    """Parse line-form ``git status --porcelain`` text into ``[(XY, path)]``.

    The newline-separated sibling of ``_parse_porcelain_z``: each entry
    line is ``XY<space><path>`` (validated against the same pattern the
    sniffer uses; anything else is skipped). A rename/copy (``X`` is
    ``R``/``C``) carries an inline ``old -> new`` arrow — the new path is
    kept, matching the ``-z`` parser. Paths git C-quoted are left
    verbatim.
    """
    rows = []
    for line in text.splitlines():
        plain = _SGR_RE.sub('', line)
        if not _PORCELAIN_LINE_RE.match(plain):
            continue
        xy, path = plain[:2], plain[3:]
        if xy[0] in 'RC' and ' -> ' in path:
            path = path.split(' -> ', 1)[1]
        rows.append((xy, path))
    return rows


# Human ``git status`` section headers → the porcelain side they stand for.
_HUMAN_SECTIONS = {
    'Changes to be committed:': 'staged',
    'Changes not staged for commit:': 'unstaged',
    'Untracked files:': 'untracked',
    'Unmerged paths:': 'unmerged',
}

# Human entry verb → one-letter status (the porcelain column letter).
_HUMAN_VERB_LETTER = {
    'modified': 'M',
    'new file': 'A',
    'deleted': 'D',
    'renamed': 'R',
    'copied': 'C',
    'typechange': 'T',
}


def _parse_human_status(text):
    """Parse human ``git status`` prose into porcelain-style ``[(XY, path)]``.

    Tracks the current section by its header line (``_HUMAN_SECTIONS``)
    and reads the tab-indented entry lines under it — the hint lines
    (``(use "git …)``) are space-indented and fall through harmlessly.
    Staged entries synthesize ``X<space>`` codes, unstaged ``<space>Y``,
    untracked ``??``, and any unmerged entry ``UU`` (the exact unmerged
    pair is not recoverable from the prose; ``UU`` keeps the conflict
    classification + ``U`` tag). Renames/copies keep the new path. A
    clean-tree status has no sections → ``[]`` → the existing "working
    tree clean" sentinel.
    """
    rows = []
    section = None
    for line in text.splitlines():
        plain = _SGR_RE.sub('', line)
        if not plain.startswith('\t'):
            section = _HUMAN_SECTIONS.get(plain.strip(), section)
            continue
        if section is None:
            continue
        entry = plain[1:]
        if section == 'untracked':
            rows.append(('??', entry))
            continue
        verb, sep, path = entry.partition(':')
        verb, path = verb.strip(), path.strip()
        if not sep:
            continue
        if verb in ('renamed', 'copied') and ' -> ' in path:
            path = path.split(' -> ', 1)[1]
        if section == 'unmerged':
            rows.append(('UU', path))
            continue
        letter = _HUMAN_VERB_LETTER.get(verb)
        if letter is None:
            continue
        rows.append((f'{letter} ' if section == 'staged' else f' {letter}',
                     path))
    return rows


def _ingest_stdin():
    """Slurp + sniff + parse stdin for ``browse-git -`` (pre-run).

    Reads ``sys.stdin`` to EOF before the Browser starts — fd 0 is still
    whatever the caller provided, so a pipe is consumed and a tty blocks
    cat-like until ^D. The content type is sniffed from the first
    non-blank line and the text parsed into the module ``_STDIN_*``
    state that the root builders / previews serve; the slurped text is
    the ONLY data source in this mode and git is never run for it.
    Empty or unrecognized input is fatal: a clean message on stderr +
    exit 2, before any UI exists.
    """
    global _STDIN_KIND, _STDIN_ROWS, _STDIN_BLOCKS
    text = sys.stdin.read()
    kind = _sniff_stdin_kind(text)
    if kind is None:
        reason = ('empty stdin input' if not text.strip() else
                  'unrecognized stdin input — expected git diff, log, '
                  'or status output')
        sys.stderr.write(f'browse-git: {reason}\n')
        sys.exit(2)
    if kind == 'diff':
        _STDIN_ROWS, _STDIN_BLOCKS = _parse_stdin_diff(text)
    elif kind == 'log':
        _STDIN_ROWS, _STDIN_BLOCKS = _parse_stdin_log(text)
    elif kind == 'porcelain':
        # The NUL ``-z`` form parses with the existing porcelain parser.
        _STDIN_ROWS = (_parse_porcelain_z(text) if '\x00' in text
                       else _parse_porcelain_lines(text))
    else:  # 'human'
        _STDIN_ROWS = _parse_human_status(text)
    _STDIN_KIND = 'status' if kind in ('porcelain', 'human') else kind


def _stdin_diff_root():
    """Piped-diff root: a single synthetic ``('sdiff',)`` umbrella row.

    The umbrella groups every file under one stats row (title
    ``diff: N files +X -Y`` with the totals colored — green ``+X`` / red
    ``-Y``; preview the synthesised stat table) so the tree gains a
    summary at the top while navigation is unchanged — ``main()``
    auto-expands it on startup (the same posted-expand the single-doc
    convention uses) so the file rows are visible immediately. Its
    children are the per-file ``('sfile', …)`` leaves
    (``_stdin_diff_files``).

    The title carries raw SGR for its ``+X`` / ``-Y`` (the same git diff
    colors the preview uses): browse-git already renders SGR embedded in
    row text — the commit graph column does — so the framework
    (``default_row_content`` → ``_normalize_content`` keeps the segment's
    SGR, ``_write_segments`` truncates it ANSI-aware and adds a trailing
    reset). The codes are zero-width, so list-row width math is unchanged.
    """
    added = removed = 0
    for i in range(len(_STDIN_ROWS)):
        a, r, _bin = _diff_block_counts(_STDIN_BLOCKS[i])
        added += a
        removed += r
    n = len(_STDIN_ROWS)
    files_word = 'file' if n == 1 else 'files'
    title = (f'diff: {n} {files_word} '
             f'{_GREEN}+{added}{_RESET} {_RED}-{removed}{_RESET}')
    return [Item(id=('sdiff',), title=title, has_children=True)]


def _stdin_diff_files():
    """The piped-diff umbrella's children: one ``('sfile', i, path)`` leaf
    per file block.

    Mirrors the commit file list's row shape (path title + colored
    status-letter tag); the leaf preview is the file's own block from
    the slurped text. Rebuilt from the parsed ``_STDIN_ROWS`` on every
    (re)list — reload re-serves the parse.
    """
    return [Item(id=('sfile', i, path), title=path,
                 tag=letter,
                 tag_style=_STATUS_LETTER_STYLE.get(letter, ''),
                 has_children=False)
            for i, (letter, path) in enumerate(_STDIN_ROWS)]


def _stdin_log_root():
    """Piped-log root: one ``('slog', i)`` leaf per commit block.

    The rows reuse the commit-row column conventions (short sha / author
    / date columns + decoration chips via ``git_row_content``); the
    decorations parse with ``remotes=set()`` so no git runs — a
    remote-tracking ref styles as a local branch, the one concession.
    Leaves: the per-commit file drill-down would need git; the whole
    block is the preview instead.
    """
    items = []
    for i, (sha, author, date, subject, deco) in enumerate(_STDIN_ROWS):
        item = Item(id=('slog', i), title=subject, has_children=False)
        item.col_sha = sha[:7]
        item.col_author = author
        item.col_date = date
        item.chips = _parse_decorations(deco, remotes=set())
        items.append(item)
    return items


def _stdin_log_preview(i):
    """Piped-log preview: the commit's own block from the slurped text.

    A block carrying patch content (``log -p``) goes through the same
    delta pipeline as a repo diff; plain / --stat blocks are returned
    verbatim (stat output is not a diff — matching ``_commit_preview``).
    """
    block = _STDIN_BLOCKS[i]
    if re.search(r'^diff --git ', _SGR_RE.sub('', block), flags=re.MULTILINE):
        return _colorize_diff(block)
    return block


# ---- children ------------------------------------------------------------


def get_children(item_id, *, reload=False):
    # Every id is a tagged tuple (``id[0]`` is the kind), or ``None`` for the
    # root. Routing is a flat ``id[0]`` dispatch with direct field access — no
    # substring scans, no ordering hazards.
    if item_id is None:
        return _root_children()
    if not isinstance(item_id, tuple) or not item_id:
        return []
    kind = item_id[0]
    if kind == 'commit':
        # A commit drills into its files; when its MESSAGE references one or
        # more ``.md`` files resolving in the commit tree, a ``[md]
        # References`` umbrella is prepended (``_commit_md_prefix``).
        return _commit_md_prefix(item_id[1]) + _commit_files(item_id[1])
    if kind == 'md-refs':
        # The ``[md] References`` umbrella under a commit — its launcher rows.
        # id = ('md-refs', sha).
        return _commit_md_children(item_id[1])
    if kind == 'reflog':
        # A reflog entry drills into the same file list as a commit —
        # a sha is a sha. id = ('reflog', n, sha).
        return _commit_files(item_id[2])
    if kind == 'file' and len(item_id) == 3 and _md_launchable(item_id[2]):
        # A committed ``.md`` file leaf expands into its single ``→ browse``
        # launcher child, extracted from the commit. id = ('file', sha, path).
        return _md_file_children(item_id, ('blob', item_id[1], item_id[2]))
    if kind == 'status' and len(item_id) == 3 and _md_launchable(item_id[2]):
        # A working-tree / untracked ``.md`` leaf expands into a ``→ browse``
        # launcher opening the real on-disk file by PATH (the working copy is
        # the live document). id = ('status', xy, path).
        root = _repo_root()
        abspath = os.path.join(root, item_id[2]) if root else item_id[2]
        return _md_file_children(item_id, ('wtfile', abspath))
    if kind == 'stash' and len(item_id) == 3 and _md_launchable(item_id[2]):
        # A stashed ``.md`` file leaf expands into a ``→ browse`` launcher
        # extracted from the stash blob. id = ('stash', n, path).
        return _md_file_children(
            item_id, ('blob', f'stash@{{{item_id[1]}}}', item_id[2]))
    if kind == 'stash' and len(item_id) == 2:
        # A stash node (('stash', n)) drills into its files; a stash file
        # leaf (('stash', n, path)) without a launcher has none.
        return _stash_files(item_id[1])
    if kind == 'ref':
        # A ref drills into its commits — the shared commit-log builder
        # with the refname as the sole rev. id = ('ref', refname). The
        # ref's own id namespaces its filler ids so two drilled-in refs
        # don't collide on a shared filler counter.
        return _log_items([item_id[1]], [], ns=item_id)
    if kind == 'worktree':
        # A worktree row drills into its branch's commits via the same
        # commit-log seam as a ref. id = ('worktree', abspath, label) where
        # label is the branch short-name, or the HEAD sha for a detached
        # worktree — either way a valid rev. (A bare worktree's label is
        # ``(bare)`` and the row is built as a leaf, so it never reaches
        # here.) The id namespaces this build's filler ids so two
        # drilled-in worktrees don't share a counter.
        return _log_items([item_id[2]], [], ns=item_id)
    if kind == 'wc':
        # A worktree-status group drills into its files. id = ('wc',
        # bucket); scope by the same positional paths as the root.
        return _worktree_files(item_id[1], _paths)
    if kind == 'sdiff':
        # The piped-diff umbrella drills into its per-file leaves.
        # id = ('sdiff',).
        return _stdin_diff_files()
    # file / status / sfile / slog leaves and filler / error / sentinel
    # rows have no children.
    return []


def _root_children():
    """Top-level rows for the active mode (stdin kind first, then ``_mode``)."""
    if _STDIN_KIND == 'diff':
        return _stdin_diff_root()
    if _STDIN_KIND == 'log':
        return _stdin_log_root()
    if _STDIN_KIND == 'status':
        # The shared status builder, fed from the parsed stdin rows.
        return _status_root()
    if _mode == 'commits':
        return _commits_root()
    if _mode == 'reflog':
        return _reflog_root()
    if _mode == 'status':
        return _status_root()
    if _mode == 'stash':
        return _stash_root()
    if _mode == 'branches':
        return _branches_root()
    if _mode == 'worktrees':
        return _worktrees_root()
    return []


def _commits_root():
    """Commits-mode root = worktree status groups + the ``git log``.

    The synthetic worktree-status rows (``_worktree_groups``) are prepended
    ONLY when the log is the plain HEAD log — no positional rev and no
    ``--all``, either of which moves the log off HEAD's history, where live
    working-tree rows would be misleading. A path filter is still honored
    (passed through to both the groups and the log), so e.g. ``browse-git
    src/`` shows the working-tree changes under ``src/`` above its commit
    history.

    ``--all`` (``_all_branches``) appends git log's ``--branches`` selector
    to the revs, spanning the log over every local branch — equivalent to
    passing all branch names positionally (and unioned with any explicit
    rev). The commit portion goes through the ``_log_items`` seam so it
    honors tree mode (the ``--tree`` graph column) exactly as the ref
    drill-down does; the synthetic rows are not commits and carry no graph
    art.
    """
    revs = list(_revs)
    if _all_branches:
        revs.append('--branches')
    items = []
    if not revs:
        items.extend(_worktree_groups(_paths))
    items.extend(_log_items(revs, _paths, ns='root'))
    return items


def _log_items(revs, paths, ns):
    """Build the commit-log rows for ``revs`` / ``paths``, honouring tree mode.

    The single seam shared by commits-mode root and the branches-mode ref
    drill-down: when ``_tree_mode`` is on it routes to the ``git log
    --graph`` builder (commit rows + meta filler rows carrying the graph
    art); otherwise it calls the plain ``_commit_log_items`` so the
    tree-off output is byte-identical to before this feature.

    ``ns`` is a stable per-build namespace key (``'root'`` for the
    commits-mode log, the ref item's id for a ref drill-down) that scopes
    the graph builder's filler ids (the ``ns`` field of ``('filler', ns,
    n)``) so concurrent builds (multiple drilled-in refs) can't collide on a
    shared filler counter. It's only consulted in tree mode; the plain
    builder takes no namespace.
    """
    if _tree_mode:
        return _commit_graph_items(revs, paths, ns)
    return _commit_log_items(revs, paths)


def _worktree_status(paths):
    """``git status --porcelain -z`` rows as ``[(XY, path)]``, scoped by paths.

    Returns the parsed ``_parse_porcelain_z`` rows on success. On any git
    failure it returns ``[]`` — degrading quietly to "no worktree rows"
    rather than injecting an error row at the top of the commit log.
    """
    args = ['status', '--porcelain', '-z']
    if paths:
        args += ['--', *paths]
    result = _run_git(*args)
    if result.returncode != 0:
        return []
    return _parse_porcelain_z(result.stdout)


# One linked-or-main worktree, as parsed from ``git worktree list
# --porcelain``: ``path`` is absolute, ``head`` the checked-out sha,
# ``branch`` the short branch name (``None`` when detached or bare), and
# ``is_main`` marks the first stanza (git always emits the main worktree
# first). The shared foundation for the worktree-aware branch/status work.
_Worktree = namedtuple('_Worktree', 'path head branch is_main')


def _parse_worktree_list(text):
    """Parse ``git worktree list --porcelain`` text into ``[_Worktree]``.

    The porcelain output is blank-line-separated stanzas, one per worktree::

        worktree <abspath>
        HEAD <sha>
        branch refs/heads/<name>      # or 'detached', or 'bare'

    Each ``worktree`` line opens a stanza; ``HEAD`` / ``branch`` fill it; a
    ``detached`` or ``bare`` line leaves ``branch`` as ``None``. The
    ``refs/heads/`` prefix is stripped to the short name. The FIRST stanza
    is the main worktree (``is_main=True``); the rest are linked. Pure: no
    git call, so it unit-tests against sample text.
    """
    worktrees = []
    path = head = branch = None
    first = True

    def _flush():
        nonlocal path, head, branch, first
        if path is not None:
            worktrees.append(_Worktree(path, head, branch, first))
            first = False
        path = head = branch = None

    for line in text.splitlines():
        if not line:
            _flush()
            continue
        key, _, value = line.partition(' ')
        if key == 'worktree':
            _flush()                       # close any unterminated stanza
            path = value
        elif key == 'HEAD':
            head = value
        elif key == 'branch':
            branch = value[len('refs/heads/'):] if value.startswith(
                'refs/heads/') else value
        # 'detached' / 'bare' (and any other key) leave branch=None.
    _flush()                               # trailing stanza (no blank line)
    return worktrees


def _worktrees():
    """All worktrees (main first) via ``git worktree list --porcelain``.

    Returns ``_parse_worktree_list`` records on success; degrades to ``[]``
    on any git failure (missing binary, bare/odd repo) like
    ``_worktree_status`` — callers treat "no worktree info" as "nothing to
    annotate" rather than surfacing an error.
    """
    result = _run_git('worktree', 'list', '--porcelain')
    if result.returncode != 0:
        return []
    return _parse_worktree_list(result.stdout)


def _worktree_relpath(abspath, main_root):
    """``abspath`` relative to the main worktree root (the main root -> '.').

    Just ``os.path.relpath`` — yields ``.claude/worktrees/foo`` for a nested
    linked worktree or ``../sibling`` for a sibling one; the main worktree
    itself maps to ``.`` (``relpath`` of a path against itself).
    """
    return os.path.relpath(abspath, main_root)


def _worktrees_root():
    """Worktrees-mode root = one ``('worktree', abspath, label)`` row each.

    From ``_worktrees()`` (main first), each row is titled ``<relpath>
    <label>`` — the path relative to the main worktree root (the main
    worktree itself is ``.``) followed by the checked-out branch short-name,
    the short HEAD sha for a detached worktree, or ``(bare)`` for a bare
    worktree (which has no HEAD line in the porcelain). For a branch or
    detached worktree ``label`` doubles as the drill-down rev (see the
    ``worktree`` branch of ``get_children``), so a detached worktree drills
    via its sha; a bare worktree has nothing to log and is a non-expandable
    leaf. Main vs linked is tagged with a small ``main`` / ``linked`` chip.
    Degrades to an error row on git failure (empty ``_worktrees()``),
    mirroring the other roots.
    """
    worktrees = _worktrees()
    if not worktrees:
        return _err_item('git worktree list failed')
    main_root = next((wt.path for wt in worktrees if wt.is_main), None)
    items = []
    for wt in worktrees:
        if wt.branch is not None:
            label = wt.branch
        elif wt.head is not None:
            label = wt.head[:7]          # detached: short HEAD sha
        else:
            label = '(bare)'             # bare worktree: no HEAD to show
        relpath = (_worktree_relpath(wt.path, main_root)
                   if main_root is not None else wt.path)
        kind = 'main' if wt.is_main else 'linked'
        items.append(Item(id=('worktree', wt.path, label),
                          title=f'{relpath} {label}',
                          tag=kind,
                          tag_style='green' if wt.is_main else 'magenta',
                          # Only branch/detached rows have a rev to log; a
                          # bare worktree (no branch, no HEAD) is a leaf.
                          has_children=bool(wt.branch or wt.head)))
    return items


def _worktree_groups(paths):
    """Synthetic worktree-group rows for the commits-mode root.

    Classifies ``_worktree_status(paths)`` into the four ``_WC_GROUPS``
    buckets and emits one expandable ``('wc', bucket)`` row per NON-empty
    bucket, in ``_WC_GROUPS`` order, titled by the group label. A clean
    tree (no changes) yields ``[]`` — no rows at all.

    Each row carries empty ``col_sha`` / ``col_author`` / ``col_date``
    strings so ``git_row_content`` aligns its label under the sibling
    commit subjects (empty columns pad to the commit column widths)
    instead of rendering flush-left.
    """
    buckets = _classify_worktree(_worktree_status(paths))
    items = []
    for bucket, label in _WC_GROUPS:
        if buckets[bucket]:
            item = Item(id=('wc', bucket), title=label, has_children=True)
            # Empty leading columns so git_row_content pads them to the
            # commit column widths — the label then lines up under the
            # commit subjects rather than at the start of the row.
            item.col_sha = ''
            item.col_author = ''
            item.col_date = ''
            items.append(item)
    return items


def _worktree_files(bucket, paths):
    """Files in one worktree ``bucket`` as ``('status', xy, path)`` leaves.

    Re-runs status + classify (cheap; keeps the groups self-contained) and
    returns that bucket's ``(XY, path)`` entries as the shared
    ``_status_leaf`` items. An unknown bucket name yields ``[]``.
    """
    buckets = _classify_worktree(_worktree_status(paths))
    return [_status_leaf(xy, path) for xy, path in buckets.get(bucket, [])]


def _commit_log_items(revs, paths):
    """``git log`` rows as ``('commit', sha)`` items, rendered in columns.

    Shared by commits mode (called with the positional ``_revs`` /
    ``_paths``) and branches-mode ref drill-down (called with
    ``([refname], [])``). Each record is NUL-separated ``%H %D %an %ar %s``
    (subject is a single line, so ``splitlines()`` then ``split('\\x00')``
    is unambiguous).

    The short sha, author, and relative date are stored as ``col_sha`` /
    ``col_author`` / ``col_date`` display strings — ``git_row_content``
    renders them as aligned leading columns (commits are flat under one
    parent, so the alignment is global). The subject is the title (the
    flexible last column); ``item.chips`` carries only the ref decorations
    parsed from ``%D`` (rendered between the date column and the subject).
    """
    args = ['log', '--format=%H%x00%D%x00%an%x00%ar%x00%s', '-n',
            str(_log_limit)]
    args += list(revs)
    if paths:
        args += ['--', *paths]
    result = _run_git(*args)
    if result.returncode != 0:
        return _err_item(f'git log failed: {result.stderr.strip()}')
    items = []
    for line in result.stdout.splitlines():
        if not line:
            continue
        fields = line.split('\x00')
        if len(fields) < 5:
            continue
        sha, deco, author, reldate, subject = fields[:5]
        item = Item(id=('commit', sha), title=subject, has_children=True)
        # Column display strings (read by git_row_content via max_col_width).
        item.col_sha = sha[:7]
        item.col_author = author
        item.col_date = reldate
        item.chips = _parse_decorations(deco)
        items.append(item)
    return items


def _graph_translate(art):
    """Sanitise + glyph-substitute one line of coloured ``git log --graph`` art.

    The art carries git's native ANSI colour (``--color=always``). It is
    treated as external input and first run through the shared framework
    sanitiser :func:`sanitize_ansi`, which keeps only complete SGR colour
    sequences (``\\e[…m``) and strips every other escape — so nothing but a
    colour code can ever reach the screen.

    Glyph substitution then maps git's ASCII connectors to box-drawing / block
    glyphs via the module ``_GRAPH_TABLE`` (``*``→``•``, ``|``→``│``,
    ``_``→``▁``); the diagonals ``/`` and ``\\`` pass through unchanged. The
    substitution is ANSI-safe: ``_SGR_RE`` (whose param class matches exactly
    what ``sanitize_ansi`` keeps) splits the line into SGR tokens and the plain
    runs between them, and ``str.translate`` is applied **only** to the plain
    runs — an SGR sequence is re-emitted verbatim, so a glyph is never
    substituted for a byte inside an escape and a colour run is never split.

    Internal spacing is git's lane alignment and is preserved; only trailing
    spaces are stripped (git right-pads every art cell, and a trailing run
    carries no lane information). ``rstrip`` strips whitespace only, leaving
    any trailing reset (``\\e[m``) intact; the colour codes are zero-width, so
    width / alignment math (``cell_width`` strips escapes) is unaffected.
    """
    art = sanitize_ansi(art)
    out = []
    pos = 0
    for m in _SGR_RE.finditer(art):
        if m.start() > pos:
            out.append(art[pos:m.start()].translate(_GRAPH_TABLE))
        out.append(m.group(0))                      # SGR token, verbatim
        pos = m.end()
    if pos < len(art):
        out.append(art[pos:].translate(_GRAPH_TABLE))
    return ''.join(out).rstrip()


def _commit_graph_items(revs, paths, ns):
    """``git log --graph`` rows: commit ``('commit', sha)`` items + filler rows.

    The tree-mode counterpart to ``_commit_log_items``. ``git log --graph``
    does ALL the lane assignment and prepends its art to every output line;
    we render those lines verbatim (after sanitise + glyph substitution)
    rather than re-deriving the graph. ``--color=always`` makes git colour the
    graph drawing (and the ``%D`` decorations) with its own ANSI; the SGR uses
    ``\\e``, never ``\\x1f``, so the field split below is unaffected. The
    ``\\x1f`` (unit separator) format keeps the art — which freely contains
    spaces, colour codes and ``|`` / ``/`` — unambiguously apart from the
    commit fields:

      * ``<art>\\x1f%H\\x1f%an\\x1f%ar\\x1f%s\\x1f%D`` for a commit line —
        splitting on ``\\x1f`` yields the art then the five fields;
      * a pure-art FILLER line (``|\\``, ``|/`` …) has NO separator, so the
        split yields a single element.

    Commit lines build the same columnar Item as ``_commit_log_items`` and
    additionally carry ``col_graph`` (the sanitised, coloured, translated art).
    Filler lines become ``meta=True`` Items (``id=('filler', ns, n)`` — ``n``
    is a running counter that resets per build, ``ns`` is the caller's
    namespace key making the id globally unique across builds;
    ``has_children=False``, no ``col_sha``) carrying only ``col_graph``. A
    ``('filler', …)`` tag matches no ``get_children`` / ``get_preview`` /
    action dispatch branch, so the row stays inert on every drill-down /
    preview / action path. ``meta=True`` makes the framework skip the cursor
    over the row (preventively) and never select it. git's line order (commits
    and fillers interleaved) is preserved.
    """
    args = ['log', '--graph', '--color=always',
            '--format=\x1f%H\x1f%an\x1f%ar\x1f%s\x1f%D', '-n', str(_log_limit)]
    args += list(revs)
    if paths:
        args += ['--', *paths]
    result = _run_git(*args)
    if result.returncode != 0:
        return _err_item(f'git log failed: {result.stderr.strip()}')
    items = []
    filler_n = 0
    for line in result.stdout.splitlines():
        parts = line.split('\x1f')
        if len(parts) > 1:
            # Commit line: parts[0] is the art, the rest are H/an/ar/s/D.
            art, sha, author, reldate, subject, deco = parts[:6]
            item = Item(id=('commit', sha), title=subject, has_children=True)
            item.col_sha = sha[:7]
            item.col_author = author
            item.col_date = reldate
            item.chips = _parse_decorations(deco)
            item.col_graph = _graph_translate(art)
            items.append(item)
        else:
            # Filler line: the whole line is graph art (no commit fields).
            # ``meta=True`` -> the framework skips the cursor over it and
            # never selects it; the (ns, counter) id stays unique across builds.
            item = Item(id=('filler', ns, filler_n), title='',
                        has_children=False, meta=True)
            item.col_graph = _graph_translate(line)
            items.append(item)
            filler_n += 1
    return items


# Leading-column field names per display mode (1/2/3), in render order. The
# SINGLE source of truth shared by ``git_row_content``'s commit-row emission
# and its filler-row pad, so the two can never drift: the commit row emits a
# column per field, and the filler row blank-pads the same fields' widths so
# the graph art lines up under the commit rows' graph column in every mode.
_LEAD_FIELDS = {
    3: ('col_sha', 'col_author', 'col_date'),
    2: ('col_sha',),
    1: (),
}


def git_row_content(item, ctx):
    """Columnar content for commit rows: sha | author | date | [graph] | subject.

    The LEADING columns (short sha yellow, author + relative date dim) are
    gated by ``_DISPLAY_MODE`` (the ``1`` / ``2`` / ``3`` keys, see
    ``_LEAD_FIELDS``): mode 3 emits sha+author+date, mode 2 just sha, mode 1
    none. Each emitted column is left-justified to the widest sibling value
    (``ctx.max_col_width`` over the row's parent group; commits are flat
    under one parent, so that is a global alignment) and followed by a
    two-space gap. The commit graph column is INDEPENDENT of the display
    mode: in tree mode the commit's ``col_graph`` art follows the leading
    columns in EVERY mode; then the ``%D`` decoration chips, then the subject
    (the title) LAST so a narrow pane truncates the subject rather than the
    metadata columns.

    Commit rows and the synthetic worktree-group rows carry ``col_sha``
    (the groups leave it empty so their label aligns under the commit
    subjects); worktree-group rows have no ``col_graph``, so in tree mode
    their label simply follows the leading columns.

    A tree-mode FILLER row carries ``col_graph`` but no ``col_sha``: it
    renders a single blank pad spanning the active mode's leading columns
    (so its art lines up under the commit rows' graph column in every mode)
    followed by its art. The pad and the commit-row leading columns both
    derive from ``_LEAD_FIELDS`` so they cannot drift.

    Every other row kind (status/stash/ref/file/reflog and the synthetic
    error / "clean" / "no stashes" rows) carries neither and falls back to
    the framework default content — keeping their tag chips and trailing
    decorations unchanged. Only the content region is taken over; chrome
    (tree indent + ▼/▶) stays framework-owned.

    The art (``col_graph``) carries git's own ANSI colour, so it is emitted
    as a segment with **no framework fg** (``(graph, None, False)``) — git's
    SGR shows through unmodified. The per-segment writer truncates that text
    ANSI-aware and the rule-3 conditional trailing reset (``\\e[m``) keeps the
    colour from bleeding into the subject or the next pane. The colour codes
    are zero-width (``cell_width`` strips them), so the columns stay aligned.
    """
    w = ctx.max_col_width
    lead = _LEAD_FIELDS[_DISPLAY_MODE]   # active leading columns, in order
    if getattr(item, 'col_sha', None) is None:
        graph = getattr(item, 'col_graph', None)
        if graph is None:
            return default_row_content(item, ctx)   # non-commit / synthetic row
        # Filler row: blank-pad the active mode's leading columns (same fields
        # the commit rows emit, so the art lines up under their graph column),
        # then the coloured art (git's own SGR -> fg=None so it shows through).
        pad = sum(w(field) + 2 for field in lead)
        return [(' ' * pad, None, False), (graph, None, False)]
    yfg, ybold = style('yellow')
    dfg, dbold = style('dim')
    # Short sha is yellow; author + date are dim. Only the active mode's
    # leading columns are emitted, padded to their global width + 2-space gap.
    col_style = {'col_sha': (yfg, ybold)}
    segments = [
        (cell_ljust(getattr(item, field), w(field)) + '  ',
         *col_style.get(field, (dfg, dbold)))
        for field in lead
    ]
    # Commit graph art (tree mode) between the leading columns and the chips —
    # git's own ANSI colour, so fg=None lets its SGR show through. git
    # closes each coloured connector with a reset, so the appended gap space
    # is uncoloured; rule-3 adds a trailing reset besides.
    graph = getattr(item, 'col_graph', None)
    if graph is not None:
        segments.append((graph + ' ', None, False))
    # Ref decorations between the date column and the subject.
    for text, stylename in getattr(item, 'chips', None) or ():
        cfg, cbold = style(stylename)
        segments.append((f'[{text}] ', cfg, cbold))
    segments.append((item.title, None, False))    # flexible column, last
    return segments


def _reflog_root():
    """``git reflog`` rows as ``('reflog', n, sha)`` items, decorated.

    Each record is NUL-separated ``%H %gd %cr %D %gs`` (selector, relative
    date, decoration, action subject). The id carries the 0-based
    enumeration index ``n`` (an int) for uniqueness — the reflog revisits
    the same sha, so a bare ``('reflog', sha)`` would collapse duplicate
    rows.
    """
    result = _run_git(
        'reflog', '--format=%H%x00%gd%x00%cr%x00%D%x00%gs', '-n',
        str(_log_limit))
    if result.returncode != 0:
        return _err_item(f'git reflog failed: {result.stderr.strip()}')
    items = []
    for n, line in enumerate(result.stdout.splitlines()):
        row = _reflog_row(n, line)
        if row is not None:
            items.append(row)
    return items


def _reflog_row(n, line):
    """Build one reflog Item from its enumeration index + NUL record.

    Returns ``None`` for a malformed (under-filled) line. The selector
    (``%gd``, e.g. ``HEAD@{0}``) and relative date are dim chips; the
    ``%D`` decoration reuses ``_parse_decorations``.
    """
    if not line:
        return None
    fields = line.split('\x00')
    if len(fields) < 5:
        return None
    sha, selector, reldate, deco, subject = fields[:5]
    chips = [(selector, 'dim'), (reldate, 'dim')]
    chips.extend(_parse_decorations(deco))
    item = Item(id=('reflog', n, sha), title=subject,
                tag=sha[:7], tag_style='yellow', has_children=True)
    item.chips = chips
    return item


def _status_root():
    """``git status --porcelain -z`` rows as ``('status', xy, path)`` items.

    Each entry becomes a non-expandable leaf tagged by its one-letter
    status (colored by kind); the leaf preview is the staged / worktree /
    untracked diff chosen by the ``XY`` code. A clean tree yields a single
    dim, non-drillable "working tree clean" row (sentinel id
    ``('status_clean',)``).

    The ``(XY, path)`` rows come from git in repo mode and from the
    pre-parsed stdin state in ``browse-git -`` status mode — the one
    data-source seam; everything downstream (leaves, sentinel) is shared.
    """
    if _STDIN_KIND == 'status':
        rows = _STDIN_ROWS
    else:
        result = _run_git('status', '--porcelain', '-z')
        if result.returncode != 0:
            return _err_item(f'git status failed: {result.stderr.strip()}')
        rows = _parse_porcelain_z(result.stdout)
    if not rows:
        return [Item(id=('status_clean',), title='working tree clean',
                     tag_style='dim', has_children=False)]
    return [_status_leaf(xy, path) for xy, path in rows]


def _stash_root():
    """``git stash list`` rows as ``('stash', n)`` items, decorated.

    Each record is NUL-separated ``%gd %cr %gs`` (selector, relative date,
    subject). An empty stash list yields a single dim, non-drillable "no
    stashes" row (sentinel id ``('stash_none',)`` — a distinct tag, so it
    never reaches the stash drill-down / preview paths).
    """
    result = _run_git('stash', 'list', '--format=%gd%x00%cr%x00%gs')
    if result.returncode != 0:
        return _err_item(f'git stash list failed: {result.stderr.strip()}')
    items = []
    for line in result.stdout.splitlines():
        row = _stash_row(line)
        if row is not None:
            items.append(row)
    if not items:
        return [Item(id=('stash_none',), title='no stashes',
                     tag_style='dim', has_children=False)]
    return items


def _stash_row(line):
    """Build one stash Item from a ``%gd %cr %gs`` NUL record.

    Returns ``None`` for a malformed (under-filled) line. The index ``n``
    is extracted from the ``%gd`` selector (``stash@{2}`` → ``2``, an int);
    the relative date is a dim chip and the selector becomes the yellow tag.
    """
    if not line:
        return None
    fields = line.split('\x00')
    if len(fields) < 3:
        return None
    selector, reldate, subject = fields[:3]
    n = _stash_index(selector)
    if n is None:
        return None
    item = Item(id=('stash', n), title=subject,
                tag=selector, tag_style='yellow', has_children=True)
    item.chips = [(reldate, 'dim')]
    return item


def _stash_index(selector):
    """Extract the 0-based index (int) from a ``stash@{n}`` selector, or None."""
    inner = selector.partition('{')[2].partition('}')[0]
    return int(inner) if inner.isdigit() else None


def _stash_files(n):
    """Files in stash ``n`` (int) as ``('stash', n, path)`` rows.

    Reuses ``git stash show --name-status stash@{n}`` + ``_parse_name_status``
    so each row carries its status-letter tag. Reached only for a real
    ``('stash', n)`` node — the "no stashes" sentinel is a distinct tag
    (``('stash_none',)``) that never routes here.
    """
    result = _run_git('stash', 'show', '--name-status', f'stash@{{{n}}}')
    if result.returncode != 0:
        return _err_item(f'git stash show failed: {result.stderr.strip()}')
    items = []
    for status, path in _parse_name_status(result.stdout):
        items.append(Item(id=('stash', n, path), title=path,
                          tag=status,
                          tag_style=_STATUS_LETTER_STYLE.get(status, ''),
                          has_children=_md_launchable(path)))
    return items


# Ref kind word → (tag style). Local branches cyan, remotes blue, tags
# yellow — matching the decoration-chip palette in `_parse_decorations`.
_REF_KIND_STYLE = {
    'branch': 'cyan',
    'remote': 'blue',
    'tag': 'yellow',
}


def _branches_root():
    """``git for-each-ref`` rows as ``('ref', short)`` items, tagged by kind.

    One call over ``refs/heads`` / ``refs/remotes`` / ``refs/tags``,
    newest-commit-first. The format emits the full ``%(refname)`` (for
    kind classification) and ``%(refname:short)`` (for display + id),
    NUL-separated. Each ref drills into that ref's commits.

    A local branch checked out in a SEPARATE (linked) worktree carries an
    extra magenta chip with that worktree's path relative to the main
    worktree root (e.g. ``.claude/worktrees/foo``). The main worktree's
    branch is skipped (it's HEAD here, not "elsewhere"), and remotes / tags
    never get the chip — only ``branch`` rows do. The map is keyed by short
    branch name, so a branch checked out in two linked worktrees would show
    the last one listed; git forbids that, so the key is effectively unique.
    """
    result = _run_git(
        'for-each-ref', '--sort=-committerdate',
        '--format=%(refname)%00%(refname:short)',
        'refs/heads', 'refs/remotes', 'refs/tags')
    if result.returncode != 0:
        return _err_item(f'git for-each-ref failed: {result.stderr.strip()}')
    # {short branch name -> linked worktree} for the NON-main worktrees with
    # a branch checked out; main_root anchors the displayed relative path.
    worktrees = _worktrees()
    main_root = next((wt.path for wt in worktrees if wt.is_main), None)
    linked = {wt.branch: wt for wt in worktrees
              if not wt.is_main and wt.branch is not None}
    items = []
    for line in result.stdout.splitlines():
        parsed = _parse_for_each_ref_line(line)
        if parsed is None:
            continue
        kind, short = parsed
        item = Item(id=('ref', short), title=short,
                    tag=kind, tag_style=_REF_KIND_STYLE.get(kind, ''),
                    has_children=True)
        if kind == 'branch' and short in linked and main_root is not None:
            relpath = _worktree_relpath(linked[short].path, main_root)
            item.chips = [(relpath, 'magenta')]
        items.append(item)
    return items


def _parse_for_each_ref_line(line):
    """Parse a ``%(refname)%00%(refname:short)`` line → ``(kind, short)``.

    ``kind`` is classified from the FULL refname prefix:
    ``refs/heads/`` → ``branch``, ``refs/remotes/`` → ``remote``,
    ``refs/tags/`` → ``tag``. Returns ``None`` for a blank / malformed
    line or an unrecognised namespace.
    """
    if not line:
        return None
    full, sep, short = line.partition('\x00')
    if not sep:
        return None
    if full.startswith('refs/heads/'):
        kind = 'branch'
    elif full.startswith('refs/remotes/'):
        kind = 'remote'
    elif full.startswith('refs/tags/'):
        kind = 'tag'
    else:
        return None
    return (kind, short)


def _commit_files(sha):
    """Changed files in commit ``sha`` as ``('file', sha, path)`` rows.

    Uses ``--name-status`` so each row carries its A/M/D/R status letter
    in the ``tag`` chip (colored by kind). Renames/copies display the new
    path, and the ``('file', …)`` id keys on that same new path.
    """
    result = _run_git('show', '--name-status', '--format=', sha)
    if result.returncode != 0:
        return _err_item(f'git show failed: {result.stderr.strip()}')
    items = []
    for status, path in _parse_name_status(result.stdout):
        items.append(Item(id=('file', sha, path), title=path,
                          tag=status,
                          tag_style=_STATUS_LETTER_STYLE.get(status, ''),
                          has_children=_md_launchable(path)))
    return items


# ---- preview -------------------------------------------------------------


def get_preview(item_id):
    # Flat ``id[0]`` dispatch with direct field access; root (``None``) and
    # the synthetic sentinel/error tags fall through to the empty preview.
    if not isinstance(item_id, tuple) or not item_id:
        return ''
    kind = item_id[0]
    if kind == 'commit':
        return _commit_preview(item_id[1])
    if kind == 'reflog':
        # Same as a commit node — id = ('reflog', n, sha).
        return _commit_preview(item_id[2])
    if kind == 'ref':
        # A refname resolves as a commit-ish, so the commit-node preview
        # (message + show --stat) works unchanged. id = ('ref', refname).
        return _commit_preview(item_id[1])
    if kind == 'file':
        return _file_preview(item_id[1], item_id[2])
    if kind == 'sdiff':
        # The piped-diff umbrella — a synthesised stat table (per-file
        # colored +N -M) over all files, fit to the current preview width
        # for long-path elision (re-rendered on a width change via
        # ``_on_resize``). id = ('sdiff',).
        return _stdin_diff_stat((_browser.preview_width if _browser else 0) or 80)
    if kind == 'sfile':
        # A per-file block of a piped diff — the same delta pipeline as a
        # repo diff, fed from the slurped text. id = ('sfile', i, path).
        return _colorize_diff(_STDIN_BLOCKS[item_id[1]])
    if kind == 'slog':
        # A commit block of a piped log. id = ('slog', i).
        return _stdin_log_preview(item_id[1])
    if kind == 'status':
        # id = ('status', xy, path).
        if _STDIN_KIND == 'status':
            # Piped status carries no diff text — show the entry itself.
            return f'{item_id[1]} {item_id[2]}'
        return _status_preview(item_id[1], item_id[2])
    if kind == 'wc':
        # A worktree-status group — a --stat summary of the bucket (the
        # per-file diff lives on its child leaves), scoped to the same
        # positional paths. id = ('wc', bucket).
        return _worktree_preview(item_id[1], _paths)
    if kind == 'stash':
        # id = ('stash', n) node or ('stash', n, path) leaf. The "no stashes"
        # sentinel is a distinct tag, so n is always a real int here.
        if len(item_id) == 3:
            return _stash_file_preview(item_id[1], item_id[2])
        return _stash_preview(item_id[1])
    if kind == 'launch':
        # A '→ browse' / References launcher row — preview the markdown it
        # would open, rendered like a message. id = ('launch', anchor, *spec).
        return _md_launch_preview(item_id[2:])
    if kind == 'md-refs':
        # The [md] References umbrella over a commit message's refs — show the
        # commit it groups them from. id = ('md-refs', sha).
        return _commit_preview(item_id[1])
    # root / err / status_clean / stash_none / filler kinds have no preview.
    return ''


def _commit_preview(sha):
    """Commit node preview = md2ansi(message) + colored ``show --stat``."""
    msg = _run_git('show', '-s', '--format=%B', sha)
    body = _md_message(msg.stdout.rstrip('\n')) if msg.returncode == 0 else ''
    stat = _git_color('show', '--stat', '--format=', sha)
    if body and stat:
        return f'{body}\n\n{stat}'
    return body or stat


def _file_preview(sha, path):
    """File leaf preview = colored per-file diff for ``path`` in ``sha``."""
    raw = _git_color('show', sha, '--', path)
    return _colorize_diff(raw)


def _status_preview(xy, path):
    """Status-leaf preview: the staged / worktree / untracked diff(s).

    The ``XY`` code selects the diff command(s) via ``_status_diff_plan``;
    each is run git-colored and piped through ``_colorize_diff``. A
    two-sided code (``MM``) shows both sections under ``── staged ──`` /
    ``── unstaged ──`` headers. The ``--no-index`` untracked diff exits
    non-zero by design, so its output is captured regardless of code.
    """
    plan = _status_diff_plan(xy, path)
    sections = []
    multi = len(plan) > 1
    for header, argv in plan:
        raw = _git_color(*argv)
        body = _colorize_diff(raw)
        if multi:
            sections.append(f'── {header} ──\n{body}')
        else:
            sections.append(body)
    return '\n\n'.join(s for s in sections if s)


def _worktree_preview(bucket, paths):
    """``--stat`` summary for a worktree ``bucket``, scoped to its files.

    Mirrors the commit-node preview (``git show --stat``): the bucket row
    summarises its changed files and the per-file diff lives on the child
    ``('status', …)`` leaves (``_status_preview``), so a worktree group
    drills down exactly like a commit. ``_classify_worktree`` scopes each
    bucket's paths so e.g. the tracked summary never pulls in staged-only
    files. The stat command is chosen by bucket:

      * ``staged``    → ``diff --cached --stat -- <bucket paths>``
      * ``tracked``   → ``diff --stat -- <bucket paths>``
      * ``conflicts`` → ``diff --stat -- <bucket paths>``
      * ``untracked`` → ``_untracked_stat`` (per-file ``diff --no-index
        --stat`` combined, since untracked files have no index entry)

    Stat output is git-colored via ``_git_color`` and returned as-is — NOT
    piped through ``_colorize_diff`` / ``delta``, which renders diffs, not
    stats (again matching ``_commit_preview``). Returns ``''`` for an empty
    bucket or an unknown name.
    """
    buckets = _classify_worktree(_worktree_status(paths))
    bucket_paths = [path for _xy, path in buckets.get(bucket, [])]
    if not bucket_paths:
        return ''
    if bucket == 'staged':
        return _git_color('diff', '--cached', '--stat', '--', *bucket_paths)
    if bucket in ('tracked', 'conflicts'):
        return _git_color('diff', '--stat', '--', *bucket_paths)
    if bucket == 'untracked':
        return _untracked_stat(bucket_paths)
    return ''


def _untracked_stat(paths):
    """Combined ``--stat`` summary for untracked files.

    Untracked files have no index entry, so each is statted on its own via
    ``diff --no-index --stat`` against ``/dev/null`` (git takes only two
    paths per invocation). git prefixes each file line with a ``/dev/null
    => `` rename arrow and prints a per-file ``N file changed`` footer; the
    arrow is stripped and the per-file footers are dropped in favour of one
    combined footer, so the bucket reads as a single cohesive stat like the
    staged / tracked buckets. Because the per-file calls can't align the
    ``|`` column the way a single ``git diff --stat`` would, the path column
    is re-padded here (``cell_ljust`` to the widest path). The ``+`` bars
    stay git-colored; the synthesised footer is plain (git's stat footer is
    uncolored too).
    """
    rows = []          # (left = ' path', right = 'N <bars>') split at ' | '
    insertions = 0
    for path in paths:
        raw = _git_color('diff', '--no-index', '--stat', '--', '/dev/null',
                         path)
        for line in raw.splitlines():
            plain = _SGR_RE.sub('', line)
            if re.match(r'\s*\d+ files? changed', plain):
                continue                       # per-file footer — re-synthesised
            if ' | ' not in plain:
                continue                       # blank / stray line
            left, _, right = line.replace(
                ' /dev/null => ', ' ', 1).rpartition(' | ')
            rows.append((left, right))
            m = re.match(r'\s*(\d+)\b', _SGR_RE.sub('', right))
            if m:
                insertions += int(m.group(1))
    if not rows:
        return ''
    width = max(cell_width(left) for left, _ in rows)
    out = [f'{cell_ljust(left, width)} | {right}' for left, right in rows]
    n = len(rows)
    files_word = 'file' if n == 1 else 'files'
    ins_word = 'insertion' if insertions == 1 else 'insertions'
    out.append(f' {n} {files_word} changed, {insertions} {ins_word}(+)')
    return '\n'.join(out)


def _stash_preview(n):
    """Stash node preview = colored ``stash show --stat stash@{n}`` summary.

    Mirrors the commit-node preview: the stash row summarises its files and
    the per-file diff lives on the child ``('stash', n, path)`` leaves
    (``_stash_file_preview``). ``--stat`` excludes untracked entries exactly
    like the ``--name-status`` children (``_stash_files``), so the summary
    and the drill-down list stay consistent. Returned as-is — NOT piped
    through ``_colorize_diff`` / ``delta`` (a diff renderer)."""
    return _git_color('stash', 'show', '--stat', f'stash@{{{n}}}')


def _stash_file_preview(n, path):
    """Stash file leaf preview = colored per-file diff in ``stash@{n}``."""
    raw = _git_color('show', f'stash@{{{n}}}', '--', path)
    return _colorize_diff(raw)


# ---- key handlers --------------------------------------------------------


def on_enter(ctx):
    """Launch a ``[md ↗]`` row, else flip expand/collapse; never quits/prints.

    A launcher row (id ``('launch', anchor, *spec)``) opens its target in
    ``browse-md`` via ``md_doc.launch`` — the ``spec`` (``id[2:]``) decides
    HOW: ``('blob', rev, path)`` extracts ``git show rev:path`` and pipes it on
    stdin (a committed / stashed / message-referenced doc need not exist on
    disk); ``('wtfile', abspath)`` opens the on-disk working-tree file by path.
    ``--root`` is the repo root so links inside the opened document resolve
    against the repo. Every other row keeps the expand/collapse toggle: leaves
    are a no-op, and a second Enter on an open row folds it back up
    (``ctx.state.expanded`` is the open-id set in the current scope).
    """
    item = ctx.cursor
    if item is None:
        return
    if isinstance(item.id, tuple) and item.id and item.id[0] == 'launch':
        _md_launch(ctx, item.id[2:])
        return
    if not item.has_children:
        return
    if item.id in ctx.state.expanded:
        ctx.collapse(item.id)
    else:
        # User-driven navigation — autoscroll the newly-revealed children
        # into view, matching the built-in Right-arrow handler.
        ctx.expand(item.id, autoscroll=True)


def _md_launch(ctx, spec):
    """Open the document a launcher-row ``spec`` points at in ``browse-md``.

    ``spec`` is the opaque tuple this recipe encoded onto the launcher id
    (``id[2:]``); its leading discriminator chooses the delivery md_doc owns:

      * ``('blob', rev, path)``  — ``git show rev:path`` content, launched on
        stdin (``rev`` is a commit sha or ``stash@{n}``). A blob that no longer
        resolves flashes instead of opening an empty document.
      * ``('wtfile', abspath)``  — the on-disk working-tree file, by path.

    ``--root`` is anchored at the repo root so references inside the opened
    document resolve the same way they do in the repo. A no-op (guarded flash)
    when md_doc is unavailable or the spec is unrecognised.
    """
    if _md_doc is None or not spec:
        return
    root = _repo_root()
    roots = (root,) if root else ()
    kind = spec[0]
    if kind == 'wtfile':
        _md_doc.launch(ctx, path=spec[1], roots=roots)
        return
    if kind == 'blob':
        rev, path = spec[1], spec[2]
        text = _blob_text(rev, path)
        if text is None:
            ctx.flash(f'cannot read {path} at {rev}')
            return
        _md_doc.launch(ctx, content=text, label=path, roots=roots)


def switch_mode(ctx):
    """Backtick — pick one of the six modes, then re-list the root.

    In stdin mode (``browse-git -``) every other view would re-run git,
    which piped input forbids — flash and stay put instead.
    """
    global _mode
    if _STDIN_KIND is not None:
        ctx.flash('mode switch not available for piped input')
        return
    chosen = ctx.pick('mode', list(_MODES))
    if chosen is None or chosen == _mode:
        return
    _mode = chosen
    ctx.flash(f'mode: {_mode}')
    # All six modes share one root scope (and thus one ``state.expanded``
    # set); drop the previous mode's expanded ids before re-listing so the
    # refresh doesn't re-fetch / re-expand rows that don't exist here.
    ctx.collapse_all()
    ctx.refresh()


def edit_file(ctx):
    """``E`` — open the real working-tree file in $EDITOR.

    Only file/status rows (and a piped diff's file rows) map to a
    working-tree path; other row kinds (commits, refs, stashes) are a
    no-op. ``('file', …)`` paths are repo-root relative, so resolve them
    against the work-tree root — outside a repo (possible in stdin mode)
    the rev-parse fails and the path opens cwd-relative.
    """
    item = ctx.cursor
    if item is None or not isinstance(item.id, tuple):
        return
    # ('file', sha, path) / ('status', xy, path) / ('sfile', i, path) all
    # carry the path at id[2].
    if item.id[0] in ('file', 'status', 'sfile'):
        path = item.id[2]
    else:
        return
    root = _run_git('rev-parse', '--show-toplevel')
    base = root.stdout.strip() if root.returncode == 0 else ''
    target = os.path.join(base, path) if base else path
    editor = os.environ.get('EDITOR', 'vi')
    ctx.run_external([editor, target])


def toggle_md(ctx):
    """``m`` — flip md2ansi coloring of the commit message; refresh preview."""
    global _MD_COLOR
    _MD_COLOR = not _MD_COLOR
    ctx.drop_preview_cache()
    ctx.flash(f'message coloring: {"colored" if _MD_COLOR else "raw"}')


# One-line labels for each display mode, used in the switch flash.
_MODE_LABELS = {
    3: 'sha · author · date · subject',
    2: 'sha · subject',
    1: 'subject only',
}


def _set_display_mode(ctx, mode):
    """Switch the leading-column set to ``mode`` (1/2/3), flash it, and refresh.

    The mode only changes which leading columns ``git_row_content`` emits (the
    strings are already on every commit Item), so a refresh is enough to
    repaint the rows at the new widths — no refetch of the log needed.
    """
    global _DISPLAY_MODE
    _DISPLAY_MODE = mode
    ctx.flash(f'display: {_MODE_LABELS[mode]}')
    ctx.refresh()


def toggle_tree(ctx):
    """``t`` — flip the commit-graph column (``--tree``); re-list the root.

    Toggles ``_tree_mode`` and refreshes the root so the commit log is
    rebuilt through the now-current builder — adding (or dropping) git's
    graph column and the interleaved filler rows. Affects commits mode and
    the branches-mode ref drill-down; other modes ignore the flag. In
    stdin mode the graph would need ``git log --graph`` — flash instead.
    """
    global _tree_mode
    if _STDIN_KIND is not None:
        ctx.flash('commit graph not available for piped input')
        return
    _tree_mode = not _tree_mode
    ctx.flash(f'commit graph: {"on" if _tree_mode else "off"}')
    ctx.refresh()


def _on_resize(ctx, cols, rows):
    """Drop the preview cache when a resize changes a width-dependent preview.

    Fires on any pane-layout change (terminal resize, split, list-ratio).
    Two previews depend on the preview width:

      * a per-file delta diff — only through delta: side-by-side turns on
        at ``width >= 160`` and its two columns re-flow with the pane (see
        ``_colorize_diff``). Its unified output (both widths < 160) does
        not depend on width.
      * the piped-diff ``('sdiff',)`` umbrella's stat table — a long
        path is front-elided to the preview width (``_stdin_diff_stat``),
        so ANY width change re-fits it, with or without delta.

    So on a genuine width change (``prev`` recorded, ``cur != prev``):
    when the delta layout flips (delta present and ``cur``/``prev``
    straddles or sits at 160) drop the WHOLE (width-agnostic) preview
    cache — every diff preview re-renders; otherwise, in piped-diff mode,
    drop ONLY the umbrella's entry (``drop_preview_cache(('sdiff',))``) —
    the stat is the one preview that re-flows on a unified-range change,
    and the per-file delta/verbatim previews stay warm. Everything else
    is left cached: the first fire just records the baseline (the startup
    preview is already at the current width); a same-width fire (a
    height-only resize the broadened hook also emits) and a unified-only
    width change with no piped diff leave the cache intact. ``_prev_pw``
    is main-thread only: ``on_resize`` fires from the run loop.
    """
    global _prev_pw
    cur = ctx.preview_width or 0
    prev, _prev_pw = _prev_pw, cur
    if prev is None or cur == prev:
        return
    if HAVE_DELTA and (cur >= 160 or prev >= 160):
        ctx.drop_preview_cache()
    elif _STDIN_KIND == 'diff':
        ctx.drop_preview_cache(('sdiff',))


# ---- context menu --------------------------------------------------------
#
# A right-click / `` ` ``-F1 menu over the cursor's git object, branching on
# its KIND (``id[0]``). Following the pilot convention (browse-ps): a PURE
# ``context_menu_options(ctx)`` builds the ``(label, token)`` rows by kind
# (opening no modal, so it is unit-testable), a flat ``{token: handler}`` table
# (``_MENU_ACTIONS``) dispatches the chosen token, and a thin
# ``on_context_menu(ctx)`` ties the two together. Submenus (Reset ▸, Switch
# mode) are just a handler re-invoking ``ctx.menu`` / ``ctx.pick``. Hotkey
# hints are LITERAL text — menus don't parse ``&`` — so an entry duplicating a
# keybinding shows it in parens (``Edit working-tree file (E)``, the mode entry
# shows `` ` ``). Mutations route through ``_git_action`` (destructive ones gate
# on a value-mapped ``ctx.confirm``); "Show"/"Diff" actions reuse the recipe's
# existing diff/delta path and page the colored output to ``$PAGER``. The menu
# is read-only-friendly: a missing tool or a git error flashes rather than
# crashes (browse-tui swallows ``on_context_menu`` exceptions besides).


def _page_diff(ctx, argv, *, empty_msg):
    """Page the colored diff produced by ``git argv…`` through ``$PAGER``.

    The shared "show a diff" path for the commit / file / reflog / stash Show
    actions (the status entry's Diff is handled separately — its ``--no-index``
    untracked case exits non-zero by design). ``color.ui=always`` forces SGR
    even though stdout is a pipe (the same colors the preview uses), and the
    diff is piped through ``_colorize_diff`` so ``delta`` renders it when on
    PATH (and the git-colored text shows verbatim otherwise — delta-absent is
    handled there). The result is paged with ``ctx.page`` (bat / ``$PAGER``).

    A git failure (a bad ref, gitless → rc 127) surfaces via ``ctx.error``
    rather than paging the stderr as if it were a diff; a successful but empty
    diff flashes ``empty_msg`` instead of opening an empty pager.
    """
    result = _run_git('-c', 'color.ui=always', *argv)
    if result.returncode != 0:
        ctx.error((result.stderr or result.stdout).strip()
                  or f'git {argv[0]} exited {result.returncode}')
        return
    if not result.stdout.strip():
        ctx.flash(empty_msg)
        return
    ctx.page(_colorize_diff(result.stdout), lang='diff')


def _page_show(ctx, argv, *, empty_msg, lang=''):
    """Run ``git argv…`` and page its stdout; flash (don't crash) on failure.

    For the non-diff "Show"/"View" actions (a file's contents at a revision,
    file history, blame, a reflog/stash ``show``). A missing git binary folds
    into rc 127 (``_run_git``), a non-zero exit surfaces stderr via
    ``ctx.error``, and empty successful output flashes ``empty_msg``. ``lang``
    is forwarded to ``ctx.page`` for bat syntax highlighting (e.g. the file's
    extension for "View this file version").
    """
    result = _run_git(*argv)
    if result.returncode != 0:
        ctx.error((result.stderr or result.stdout).strip()
                  or f'git {argv[0]} exited {result.returncode}')
        return
    if not result.stdout.strip():
        ctx.flash(empty_msg)
        return
    ctx.page(result.stdout, lang=lang)


def _git_action(ctx, argv, *, ok_msg, confirm_msg=None, strong=False):
    """Run a mutating ``git argv…`` (optionally behind a confirm), then refresh.

    The single mutation path for the menu's history/working-tree actions
    (checkout, reset, branch/tag create + delete, cherry-pick, revert, merge,
    rebase, stage/unstage/discard, stash apply/pop/drop). When ``confirm_msg``
    is given a value-mapped Yes/No dialog gates the run (``ctx.confirm`` returns
    the mapped ``True``/``False`` so the result is used directly); cancelling
    is a no-op. ``strong=True`` flips the default button to ``No`` for the
    irreversible cases (``reset --hard``, ``discard``) so an accidental Enter
    doesn't fire them.

    On success ``ok_msg`` flashes (logged) and the list is refreshed so the new
    state shows; a git failure surfaces stderr via ``ctx.error`` and the tree
    is left untouched. Returns ``True`` iff the command ran and succeeded.
    """
    if confirm_msg is not None:
        buttons = ([('&No', False), ('&Yes', True)] if strong
                   else [('&Yes', True), ('&No', False)])
        if not ctx.confirm(confirm_msg, buttons):
            return False
    result = _run_git(*argv)
    if result.returncode != 0:
        ctx.error((result.stderr or result.stdout).strip()
                  or f'git {argv[0]} exited {result.returncode}')
        return False
    ctx.flash(ok_msg, log=True)
    ctx.refresh()
    return True


def _input_name(ctx, prompt):
    """Prompt for a ref/tag name; return the stripped value, or ``None``.

    Wraps ``ctx.input``: a cancel (esc → ``None``) or a blank/whitespace entry
    both yield ``None`` so the caller bails without running git on an empty
    name.
    """
    raw = ctx.input(prompt)
    if raw is None or not raw.strip():
        return None
    return raw.strip()


def _selected_commit_shas(ctx):
    """The shas of all currently-selected ``('commit', sha)`` rows."""
    return [it.id[1] for it in ctx.selected
            if isinstance(it.id, tuple) and len(it.id) >= 2
            and it.id[0] == 'commit']


def _one_other_commit(ctx, sha):
    """The sha of the single OTHER selected commit, or ``None``.

    Gates the commit menu's "Diff against selected" entry: enabled only when
    exactly one commit OTHER than the cursor's is in the selection. Two-plus
    other commits (ambiguous) or none yields ``None`` and the entry is omitted.
    """
    others = [s for s in _selected_commit_shas(ctx) if s != sha]
    return others[0] if len(others) == 1 else None


def _has_plan_md(sha):
    """True when ``.PLAN.md`` exists in commit ``sha``'s tree.

    Probes the COMMIT TREE (``git cat-file -e sha:.PLAN.md``), not the working
    tree — the file may be present in the commit yet absent on disk. Gates the
    commit menu's browse-plan entry; ``False`` on any git failure.
    """
    return _run_git('cat-file', '-e', f'{sha}:.PLAN.md').returncode == 0


# -- commit ('commit', sha) -------------------------------------------------


def _cm_commit_full_sha(ctx, sha):
    """Pop up the full commit SHA (the row shows only the abbreviation)."""
    ctx.alert(sha, title='commit')


def _cm_commit_checkout(ctx, sha):
    _git_action(ctx, ['checkout', sha], ok_msg=f'checked out {sha[:7]}',
                confirm_msg=f'git checkout {sha[:7]}?')


def _cm_commit_branch(ctx, sha):
    name = _input_name(ctx, f'New branch at {sha[:7]}: ')
    if name is not None:
        _git_action(ctx, ['branch', name, sha],
                    ok_msg=f'created branch {name} at {sha[:7]}')


def _cm_commit_tag(ctx, sha):
    name = _input_name(ctx, f'New tag at {sha[:7]}: ')
    if name is not None:
        _git_action(ctx, ['tag', name, sha],
                    ok_msg=f'created tag {name} at {sha[:7]}')


def _cm_commit_cherry_pick(ctx, sha):
    _git_action(ctx, ['cherry-pick', sha], ok_msg=f'cherry-picked {sha[:7]}',
                confirm_msg=f'git cherry-pick {sha[:7]}?')


def _cm_commit_revert(ctx, sha):
    # Revert mutates history (a new commit) — a destructive-class action, so
    # it confirms; ``--no-edit`` skips the editor the menu can't host inline.
    _git_action(ctx, ['revert', '--no-edit', sha],
                ok_msg=f'reverted {sha[:7]}',
                confirm_msg=f'git revert {sha[:7]}?')


# Reset ▸ submenu rows: ``(label, (mode, confirm_msg, strong))``. soft/mixed
# confirm normally; hard gets a STRONG confirm (default button No) — it
# discards working-tree changes irreversibly.
def _cm_commit_reset(ctx, sha):
    chosen = ctx.menu([
        ('soft (keep index + working tree)', 'soft'),
        ('mixed (keep working tree)', 'mixed'),
        ('hard (DISCARD working tree)', 'hard'),
    ])
    if chosen is None:
        return
    strong = chosen == 'hard'
    msg = (f'git reset --hard {sha[:7]}? This DISCARDS all '
           'uncommitted changes.' if strong
           else f'git reset --{chosen} {sha[:7]}?')
    _git_action(ctx, ['reset', f'--{chosen}', sha],
                ok_msg=f'reset --{chosen} to {sha[:7]}',
                confirm_msg=msg, strong=strong)


def _cm_commit_diff_selected(ctx, sha):
    other = _one_other_commit(ctx, sha)
    if other is None:
        ctx.flash('select exactly one other commit to diff against')
        return
    _page_diff(ctx, ['diff', other, sha],
               empty_msg=f'no differences between {other[:7]} and {sha[:7]}')


def _cm_commit_browse_plan(ctx, sha):
    """Open ``.PLAN.md`` at this commit in browse-plan (piped on stdin).

    Reached only when ``_has_plan_md`` confirmed the file is in the commit
    tree, but the extract can still fail (gitless mid-session) — flash rather
    than launch an empty document. The blob is piped to ``browse-plan -`` so
    no on-disk file is needed; a missing ``browse-plan`` on PATH surfaces via
    ``run_external``'s own error.
    """
    text = _blob_text(sha, '.PLAN.md')
    if text is None:
        ctx.flash(f'cannot read .PLAN.md at {sha[:7]}')
        return
    ctx.run_external(['browse-plan', '-'], stdin_text=text, keep_screen=True)


def context_menu_commit(ctx, item_id):
    """``(label, token)`` rows for a ``('commit', sha)`` cursor row.

    "Diff against selected" appears only when exactly one OTHER commit is
    selected (``_one_other_commit``); the browse-plan row only when the commit
    tree carries ``.PLAN.md`` (``_has_plan_md``). Reset is a submenu (``Reset
    ▸``). No hotkey hints here — none of these duplicate a global keybinding.
    """
    sha = item_id[1]
    rows = [
        ('Show full SHA', 'commit.sha'),
        ('Checkout', 'commit.checkout'),
        ('Create branch here…', 'commit.branch'),
        ('Create tag here…', 'commit.tag'),
        ('Cherry-pick', 'commit.cherry'),
        ('Revert', 'commit.revert'),
        ('Reset ▸', 'commit.reset'),
    ]
    if _one_other_commit(ctx, sha) is not None:
        rows.append(('Diff against selected', 'commit.diffsel'))
    if _has_plan_md(sha):
        rows.append(('Browse .PLAN.md at this commit', 'commit.plan'))
    return rows


# -- file in a commit ('file', sha, path) -----------------------------------


def _cm_file_view(ctx, sha, path):
    _page_show(ctx, ['show', f'{sha}:{path}'],
               empty_msg=f'{path} is empty at {sha[:7]}',
               lang=os.path.basename(path))


def _cm_file_diff(ctx, sha, path):
    _page_diff(ctx, ['show', sha, '--', path],
               empty_msg=f'no diff for {path} in {sha[:7]}')


def _cm_file_history(ctx, sha, path):
    # History of the path itself (not pinned to this commit) — the full
    # evolution, newest first, with patches.
    _page_show(ctx, ['log', '-p', '--', path],
               empty_msg=f'no history for {path}')


def _cm_file_blame(ctx, sha, path):
    _page_show(ctx, ['blame', sha, '--', path],
               empty_msg=f'no blame for {path} at {sha[:7]}')


def _file_rev(item_id):
    """The rev a file-menu row targets: a commit sha, or a stash selector.

    The file menu serves two leaf kinds — ``('file', sha, path)`` (rev is the
    commit sha at ``id[1]``) and ``('stash', n, path)`` (rev is the int ``n``
    at ``id[1]``, which git addresses as the ``stash@{n}`` selector). Mapping
    the rev here lets one set of file handlers (view / diff / history / blame)
    serve both without a kind branch in each.
    """
    return (f'stash@{{{item_id[1]}}}' if item_id[0] == 'stash'
            else item_id[1])


def context_menu_file(ctx, item_id):
    """``(label, token)`` rows for a file-menu cursor row.

    Serves a ``('file', sha, path)`` committed file and a ``('stash', n,
    path)`` stashed file alike (the rev is resolved per-id by ``_file_rev``).
    "Edit working-tree file" duplicates the ``E`` action, so its row carries
    the ``(E)`` hint. "Show full path" is always offered: the row title is the
    full path but the list renderer cell-cuts it (no ellipsis is inserted) when
    the pane is narrow, so a pop-up is the reliable way to read a long path —
    and a redundant pop-up of an already-visible short path is harmless. The
    truncated width varies per row depth / chrome, so the recipe can't cheaply
    detect "is this row clipped"; always-show beats a fragile heuristic.
    """
    return [
        ('View this file version', 'file.view'),
        ('Edit working-tree file (E)', 'file.edit'),
        ('Diff this file in this commit', 'file.diff'),
        ('File history', 'file.history'),
        ('Blame at this commit', 'file.blame'),
        ('Show full path', 'file.path'),
    ]


